update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single age focus"},{"label":"B","text":"Men''s Health Across Lifespan Integrative Primary Care"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid mental health men"},{"label":"D","text":"Only acute care"},{"label":"E","text":"No engagement strategies"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Men''s Health Across Lifespan Integrative Primary Care: (1) **Men underutilize primary care** + worse outcomes — avoidance, stigma, work-prioritization, masculinity norms; engaging is opportunity; (2) **Young adult (18-39)**: - Lifestyle: smoking + alcohol + substance use + driving safety + sexual health + STI + mental health + injury prevention; - Establish primary care relationship; - Vaccinations (HPV catch-up to 26 + shared 27-45, Tdap, flu, COVID, meningococcal college); - Reproductive health + contraception (partner) + STI screening; - Mental health screening + suicide (highest age group); - Substance use screening; - Testicular self-exam (controversial USPSTF) — awareness of CA young; - Skin cancer awareness; (3) **Middle adult (40-64)** — major chronic disease emergence: - **CV risk assessment + management**: BP screening, lipid (ASCVD risk), DM screening (35-70), statin per risk, smoking cessation, lifestyle; - **Cancer screening**: - **Colorectal** 45-75 (USPSTF lowered); - **Lung CT** 50-80 + 20 pack-year smoker; - **Prostate** 55-69 shared decision; high-risk (Black, family, BRCA) earlier; - **Skin**, **oral**, **testicular** awareness; - **DM + obesity**: screening + lifestyle intervention; DPP for prediabetes; medication including GLP-1 RA for obesity; - **Mental health**: depression + anxiety screening; suicide higher rate; substance use including alcohol; - **Sexual health**: ED screening (window to CVD), testosterone (true hypogonadism only), STI; - **Reproductive**: vasectomy counseling, fertility preservation pre-treatment; - **Workplace + occupational**: hazards, ergonomics, stress; - **Sleep**: OSA more common men; - **Vaccinations**: continue + age-based; (4) **Older adult (65+)**: - **Geriatric care principles** (see separate); - **Cancer screening individualized + life expectancy**: stop most after age 75-85 or life expectancy < 10 yr; - **CV ongoing**; - **Osteoporosis**: men 70+ (or earlier if risk — hypogonadism, glucocorticoids, antiandrogen therapy); - **Falls assessment**; - **Cognitive screening**; - **BPH + LUTS** management; - **Polypharmacy management**; - **Caregiving role**; - **Advance care planning**; - **Mental health + isolation**: widower depression; suicide elevated; (5) **Cross-lifespan issues**: - **Smoking**: leading preventable cause; cessation; - **Cardiovascular** most common cause of death; - **Mental health**: underdiagnosed + undertreated; suicide rates higher men (especially older); depression presents differently (irritability, work issues, substance, somatic); - **Substance use**: higher rates; address; - **Injury + violence**: prevention; firearms; - **Sexual + reproductive**: lifespan; - **LGBTQ+ men**: affirming care; specific health considerations; - **Men of color**: disparities (life expectancy, prostate CA — Black men higher risk, CV); cultural humility; - **Veterans**: specific exposures + mental health + trauma; PTSD; access to VA; - **Workplace + occupational**: hazards + stress + chemical exposures; - **Caregiving + family**: increasing role for men; supportive; (6) **Engagement strategies**: - Meet patients where they are; - Honest + practical; - Sports + work metaphors when fit; - Reduce stigma; - Address barriers (time, cost, access); - Use other touch points (employer, sports physical, partner appointment); - Outreach + reminders; (7) **Specific cancer awareness**: - **Testicular CA** — young men, self-exam awareness; - **Prostate CA** — shared decision PSA + family history; - **Penile CA** — uncommon but awareness; - **Male breast CA** — uncommon, family history BRCA; - **Skin CA**; - **Colorectal**; - **Lung**; (8) **Sexual + reproductive health**: - **ED** — window to CVD; - **Testosterone** — only if confirmed hypogonadism; - **Infertility** — workup + REI; - **STI** screening + prevention; - **PrEP** for high-risk; - **LGBTQ+ + MSM-specific**: see separate; (9) **Pediatric to adult transition** for young men chronic conditions; (10) **Multidisciplinary integrative**: family medicine + urology + cardiology + behavioral health + endocrinology + oncology + community + family + workplace + male-oriented programs

---

Men''s health lifespan: underutilize care — engagement strategies. Young adult — lifestyle + mental health + sexual. Middle adult — chronic disease + cancer screening + ED + mental health. Older adult — geriatric principles + BPH + falls. Cross-lifespan (CV, mental health, substance, sexual). Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยชายอายุ 45 ปี — primary care across men''s lifespan; chronic disease + screening + sexual + mental health';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single visit assessment"},{"label":"B","text":"Refugee + Immigrant Primary Care Integrative (CDC + AAFP + Society for Refugee Healthcare Providers)"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid mental health discussion"},{"label":"D","text":"Family interpreter"},{"label":"E","text":"Cultural assimilation expected"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Refugee + Immigrant Primary Care Integrative (CDC + AAFP + Society for Refugee Healthcare Providers): (1) **Categories**: refugees (UNHCR-designated), asylees, asylum-seekers, immigrants (documented + undocumented), TPS (temporary protected status), parolees, others; (2) **Pre-arrival**: - **Refugees**: medical exam abroad — TB, syphilis, gonorrhea, leprosy, HIV (not exclusionary now); - **Vaccinations** per CDC requirements; - **Domestic medical screening** comprehensive within 30-90 days arrival (state programs); (3) **Comprehensive initial assessment**: - **History**: country of origin, ethnicity, language, refugee experience (camp duration, journey), pre-migration trauma, family separation, current resettlement; - **Physical exam comprehensive**; - **Screening**: - **Infectious**: - **TB** (IGRA or TST) — high prevalence many countries; LTBI treatment; - **HBV, HCV, HIV** screening — variable by country; - **Syphilis** + STIs; - **Parasites** (stool O&P, schistosomiasis serology endemic areas, strongyloidiasis especially before steroid/biologic — empirical ivermectin for refugees from endemic some recommend); - **Malaria** endemic; - **Country-specific**: e.g., Chagas Latin America; - **Hematologic**: CBC, hemoglobinopathy screening (thalassemia + sickle cell endemic areas), G6PD before primaquine/dapsone; - **Vitamin deficiency**: D, B12, iron — high prevalence; - **Lead** (children especially); - **Mental health**: PTSD, depression, anxiety — high prevalence; refugee-specific scales (RHS-15, HSCL-25); torture history; - **Dental + oral** — often unmet; - **Vision + hearing** — refractive errors common, may be untreated; - **Reproductive health**: contraception, prenatal care, female genital cutting (sensitive assessment + management); - **Vaccinations**: catch-up per CDC schedule; document acceptance varies; (4) **Common conditions**: - **Vitamin D deficiency** very common; - **Latent TB** common; - **Mental health** PTSD, depression; - **Chronic disease** (HT, DM, CV) — often unmanaged + worsening; - **Cancer screening** often never done; - **Untreated chronic conditions**: thyroid, anemia, etc.; - **Reproductive health** unmet needs; (5) **Cultural humility + practices**: - Diverse beliefs about health + illness + body; - Religious + spiritual considerations (Ramadan, prayer times, dietary halal/kosher, modesty, gender concordance providers preferred some); - Traditional healing integration; - Family + community dynamics; - Migration trauma + ongoing acculturation stress; - Discrimination + xenophobia; (6) **Trauma-informed care**: - High prevalence trauma (torture, violence, sexual, witnessing); - Triggers in healthcare; - Safety + trust + choice + collaboration + empowerment; - PTSD screening + treatment (EMDR, CBT, medications); - **Center for Victims of Torture** + similar resources; (7) **Language access**: - **Professional interpreters** mandatory — Title VI requirement federally-funded; - Video, phone, in-person; - NOT family or children; - Cultural brokers; - Written materials in language; (8) **Legal + social complexity**: - Immigration status + healthcare access; - Public charge concerns (chilling effect on services); - Employment + housing + food + transportation; - Family reunification; - Asylum process + medical evaluation (Physicians for Human Rights training for asylum medical/psychological evaluations); - Healthcare access for undocumented limited (emergency Medicaid + community resources); (9) **Refugee-specific resources + benefits**: - **RMA (Refugee Medical Assistance)** — 8 mo healthcare benefits federally funded; - State-specific extended benefits; - Refugee Resettlement Agencies; - Community + faith-based partners; (10) **Pediatric considerations**: - Vaccinations catch-up; - Growth + nutrition; - Developmental screening; - Education + school enrollment; - Trauma in children; - Family reunification; (11) **Special populations**: - **Unaccompanied minors**: complex; - **LGBTQ+ refugees**: persecution-specific; - **Survivors of torture + trafficking**; - **Women + girls**: gender-based violence, FGC; - **Older refugees**: isolation, dependency; (12) **Long-term integration**: chronic disease management as integration progresses; cultural broker role; advocacy; (13) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + community health worker / cultural broker + interpreter + behavioral health + social work + legal + community partners + religious + family + specialty referrals + public health + resettlement agencies

---

Refugee/immigrant care: comprehensive initial screening (TB, parasites, vitamin D, mental health, chronic disease). Trauma-informed essential. Cultural humility. Professional interpreters. Legal + social complexity. Refugee-specific benefits + resources. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ครอบครัวผู้อพยพ refugee — newly arrived, multiple medical + psychosocial concerns; family-centered integrative primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Individual visits only"},{"label":"B","text":"Group Visits / Shared Medical Appointments (SMA) Integrative Care"},{"label":"C","text":"Random topics"},{"label":"D","text":"No peer interaction"},{"label":"E","text":"No follow-up"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Group Visits / Shared Medical Appointments (SMA) Integrative Care: (1) **Definition**: physician-led group visit where multiple patients with similar conditions receive medical care + education + peer support together; can include other team members; (2) **Evidence**: improved outcomes T2DM, HTN, HF, depression, chronic pain, prenatal care, weight management; cost-effective; (3) **Models**: - **Drop-in Group Medical Appointment (DIGMA)**: ongoing, mixed conditions, regular schedule; - **Cooperative Health Care Clinic (CHCC)**: closed cohort same patients over time; - **Physical SMA (PSMA)**: includes individual physical exam component; - **Specialty + condition-specific**: prenatal (Centering Pregnancy), DM, HTN, HF, depression, pain, weight, smoking cessation, behavioral health; (4) **Components**: - **Group education** by team; - **Peer interaction + support**; - **Individual physician encounter** within or separate; - **Team-based care** — RN, dietitian, behavioral health, pharmacy as needed; - **Goal-setting + accountability**; - **Self-management focus**; - **Cultural + language matching** when possible; (5) **Advantages**: - **Patient**: peer support + learning, more time with provider (90 min vs 15), normalization, accountability, social connection; - **Provider**: education efficiency, address common issues once, team-based, reduced burnout; - **System**: efficiency, access, reduced ED visits + hospitalizations, cost-effective; - **Outcomes**: improved A1c, BP, adherence, self-efficacy, satisfaction; (6) **Setup considerations**: - **Space**: large enough for group + privacy; - **Time**: 90-120 min typical; - **Frequency**: weekly to monthly; - **Group size**: 6-15 typical; - **Recruitment**: screen + enroll, address transportation, scheduling; - **Confidentiality + ground rules**: HIPAA, group agreements; - **Documentation**: each individual encounter; - **Billing**: typically code each individual; some states offer specific codes; - **Technology**: virtual SMA growing — telegroups; (7) **Patient selection**: - Common diagnosis or interest; - Mix of stages (engagement + role model); - Voluntary; - Address barriers; (8) **Specific examples + evidence**: - **Centering Pregnancy** — well-established, improved birth outcomes (lower preterm + LBW), satisfaction; - **DM SMAs** — improved A1c + other markers; - **HTN SMAs**; - **Chronic pain group programs** — Living Well; - **Behavioral health groups** — depression, anxiety, mindfulness, CBT; - **Weight management** — DPP group format; - **Cardiac rehab + pulmonary rehab** — group-based; - **Substance use treatment**: AA, MAT groups; - **Smoking cessation groups**; - **CHWs + peer support** programs; (9) **Cultural + linguistic adaptation**: - Language-concordant groups; - Cultural framing of content; - Community + faith partnerships; (10) **Integration with population health management**: identify panel members + outreach + enroll; (11) **Provider training**: facilitation, group dynamics, time management; (12) **Patient engagement + sustainability**: address dropout, peer leaders, ongoing recruitment; (13) **Equity + access**: address transportation, childcare, language, cost; reach underserved; (14) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + APP + nursing + dietitian + behavioral health + pharmacy + CHW + administration + patients (peer leaders, advisors)

---

Group visits / SMA: physician-led group care with peer support. Multiple models. Evidence-based for DM, HTN, prenatal, etc. Components: education + peer + individual encounter + team. Advantages — patient, provider, system. Setup + selection + billing. Equity. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วย T2DM 12 คน — group visit model — shared medical appointments + peer support';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Refer all to specialty"},{"label":"B","text":"Behavioral Health Integration (BHI) — Collaborative Care Model (Unützer + APA + AIMS Center)"},{"label":"C","text":"No integration"},{"label":"D","text":"Random behavioral health"},{"label":"E","text":"Single provider model"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Behavioral Health Integration (BHI) — Collaborative Care Model (Unützer + APA + AIMS Center): (1) **Need**: mental health in primary care; ~ 50% mental health care delivered in primary care; specialty access limited; outcomes traditionally suboptimal; (2) **Continuum of integration** (SAMHSA-HRSA 4-quadrant): - **Level 1: Minimal collaboration** — separate; - **Level 2: Basic collaboration at distance** — referral with limited communication; - **Level 3: Basic collaboration on-site** — co-located; - **Level 4: Close collaboration on-site with shared system**; - **Level 5: Close collaboration approaching integration**; - **Level 6: Full collaboration in transformed/merged integrated practice**; - Higher level = better outcomes for moderate-severe conditions; (3) **Collaborative Care Model (CoCM)** — most evidence: - **5 core principles**: - Patient-centered team care; - Population-based care (registry); - Measurement-based care + treat-to-target (PHQ-9, GAD-7 routine); - Evidence-based care; - Accountable care; - **Team members**: - **PCP** — primary clinical management; - **Behavioral Health Care Manager** — RN, social worker, psychologist — care management, brief interventions, follow-up, registry; - **Psychiatric Consultant** — weekly case review with care manager, recommendations to PCP, direct consultation for complex; (4) **Evidence Collaborative Care**: > 80 RCTs across conditions + settings — better outcomes vs usual care for depression, anxiety, substance use, PTSD, dementia + caregiver; pediatric; perinatal; chronic disease comorbid; veterans; rural; (5) **CMS Collaborative Care codes (BHI 99492-99494)** support reimbursement; many private insurance; (6) **Implementation steps**: - Assess practice readiness; - Identify champions + leadership; - Workflow design + EHR integration; - Hire/train care manager + psychiatric consultant; - Universal screening (PHQ-9, GAD-7, CRAFFT, others); - Registry + measurement; - Quality improvement ongoing; - Patient engagement; - Reimbursement strategy; (7) **Alternative integrated models**: - **Primary Care Behavioral Health (PCBH)** — behavioral health provider embedded; brief interventions; warm handoffs; broader population; less specialized depression focus; - **Co-location** without integration — basic; - **Bidirectional integration** — primary care in mental health settings; (8) **Specific applications**: - **Depression** — most evidence; - **Anxiety**; - **PTSD + trauma**; - **Substance use disorders**: MAT for OUD (buprenorphine), AUD pharmacotherapy + counseling; - **Chronic pain + mental health comorbidity**; - **Severe mental illness** in primary care: schizophrenia, bipolar; primary care of medical comorbidities + co-management with psychiatry; - **Pediatric**: family-based, school integration; - **Perinatal**: postpartum depression; - **Geriatric**: depression, dementia, caregiver support; - **Substance use disorders**: SBIRT + MAT; - **Chronic disease**: DM + depression, etc. — depression treatment improves both; (9) **Specific evidence-based interventions delivered by BHI team**: - **Brief CBT**; - **Behavioral activation**; - **Problem-solving therapy**; - **Motivational interviewing**; - **Mindfulness**; - **Sleep hygiene + CBT-I**; - **Substance use brief intervention**; - **Self-management coaching**; (10) **Pharmacotherapy support**: PCP-prescribed with consultation; medication monitoring; adherence support; (11) **Quality measures**: PHQ-9 response + remission, GAD-7, screening rates, treatment initiation + intensification, suicide risk assessment; (12) **Equity + access**: BHI improves access to mental health especially for underserved + minorities + rural; addresses stigma; (13) **Technology**: tele-mental health, apps (Calm, Headspace, computerized CBT — Beating the Blues), digital therapeutics; (14) **Workforce considerations**: care manager workforce + training + reimbursement adequate; psychiatry workforce shortage so consultation model efficient; (15) **Resources**: AIMS Center (University of Washington), APA Integrated Care, SAMHSA-HRSA Center for Integrated Health Solutions; (16) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + behavioral health care manager + psychiatric consultant + APP + nursing + social work + community resources + family + patient + payers + leadership

---

BHI Collaborative Care Model: PCP + care manager + psychiatric consultant. 5 core principles. Strong evidence depression + anxiety + others. Implementation. Alternative models (PCBH). Specific applications + pharm + non-pharm interventions. CMS reimbursement codes. Equity. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — implementing behavioral health integration (BHI) in primary care — Collaborative Care Model';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Aggressive treatment until death"},{"label":"B","text":"End-of-Life Care Integrative Family-Centered (NHPCO + CAPC + Ariadne)"},{"label":"C","text":"No goals-of-care discussion"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid family"},{"label":"E","text":"Single specialty handles"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** End-of-Life Care Integrative Family-Centered (NHPCO + CAPC + Ariadne): (1) **Goals-of-care conversation** central + ongoing: - Reframe from disease focus to person + values; - Hopes + worries + tradeoffs framework; - ''I wish + I worry + I wonder'' phrases; - Family + caregiver involvement; - Cultural + spiritual considerations; - Document + revisit as condition changes; - Serious Illness Conversation Guide (Ariadne); (2) **Hospice eligibility + benefit**: - **Prognosis ≤ 6 mo** if disease takes natural course; - Patient + family agreement on comfort focus; - Medicare hospice benefit since 1982 — most insurance covers similarly; - **Disease-specific Local Coverage Determinations (LCDs)**: cancer, dementia, CHF, COPD, liver, kidney, stroke, debility; - **Hospice team**: physician, nurse, social worker, chaplain, aide, volunteer, bereavement counselor, therapists; - **Settings**: home (most common), nursing facility, inpatient hospice, hospital (rare); - **Levels**: routine home, continuous home, inpatient respite, general inpatient (for symptom crisis); (3) **Symptom management** — see palliative care: pain, dyspnea, nausea, constipation, fatigue, anorexia, anxiety, delirium, spiritual distress; (4) **Active dying phase**: - **Signs**: decreased consciousness, decreased intake, mottling, terminal secretions, Cheyne-Stokes breathing, restlessness, decreased urine, cool extremities; - **Anticipatory guidance** for family — expected, peaceful; - **Comfort measures**: medications for pain, dyspnea, secretions (scopolamine, glycopyrrolate); positioning; mouth care; - **Hydration / nutrition**: artificial generally not beneficial actively dying — discuss expectations; - **Discontinue non-essential medications + monitoring**; - **Withdraw burdensome interventions** as appropriate (cardiac monitor, IVs, BP checks, finger sticks); (5) **Family + caregiver support** integral: - **Pre-death**: education, anticipatory grief, emotional + practical support; - **Bedside vigil**: meaningful, supportive; - **Death**: notify family; provide privacy; honor cultural + religious practices; - **Post-death**: notify physician (or hospice MD pronounces); body care; mortuary; - **Bereavement support**: 13 months hospice (Medicare); ongoing groups + counseling; complicated grief identification + referral; (6) **Spiritual + existential care**: - **Chaplaincy** integral hospice; - **Religious + cultural practices** at end of life — diverse; ask + honor; - **Existential dignity work**: life review, dignity therapy, meaning-making, music/art, legacy; - **Mindfulness + meditation**; - **Connection + relationships**; (7) **Specific scenarios**: - **Sudden / unexpected death**: traumatic; immediate support family; followup; - **Death of child / infant**: devastating; specialized perinatal palliative + pediatric palliative; - **Suicide** (recent): family complex grief; support; reduce stigma + blame; - **Mass casualty / disaster deaths**; (8) **Voluntarily stopping eating and drinking (VSED)**: option in some patients; respect autonomy; supportive care; - **Medical aid in dying (MAID)** — legal in 10 US states + DC + several countries; differs from euthanasia (illegal US); strict eligibility + safeguards; family medicine often involved when legal + comfortable; - **Palliative sedation** for refractory suffering — ethical + accepted (not euthanasia); intentions transparent; (9) **Pediatric end-of-life**: - Specific challenges; - Family + sibling support; - Decision-making by parents — challenging; - School + community support; - Specialty pediatric palliative + hospice; (10) **Equity in end-of-life care**: - Disparities by race, ethnicity, SES, geography; - Black + Hispanic + Asian patients + families different preferences/utilization; - Cultural humility critical; - Access barriers; - Healthcare proxy + advance directives less common in some communities; (11) **Provider self-care + grief**: cumulative loss; debriefing; institutional support; primary care relationships make end-of-life care deeply meaningful + emotionally demanding; (12) **Quality measures end-of-life**: hospice length of stay (very short = late referral), preferred place of death achieved, family satisfaction; (13) **Family medicine well-positioned**: relationship continuity, family unit care, holistic, comfort with whole-person care; (14) **Multidisciplinary integrative**: PCP + hospice MD + RN + SW + chaplain + aide + volunteer + family + extended family + community + religious community + bereavement + pediatric (if pediatric)

---

End-of-life integrative: goals-of-care central. Hospice for ≤ 6 mo prognosis. Active dying signs + management. Family + caregiver support throughout. Spiritual + existential. VSED / MAID where legal. Pediatric. Equity. Provider self-care. Family medicine well-positioned. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 78 ปี — advanced cancer + life expectancy < 6 mo + family + spiritual + goals-of-care + hospice transition';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Stop all medications immediately"},{"label":"B","text":"Outpatient Hyperkalemia Management"},{"label":"C","text":"Ignore — asymptomatic"},{"label":"D","text":"Send to ER routinely all K > 5.5"},{"label":"E","text":"Increase ACEi for renal protection"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Outpatient Hyperkalemia Management: (1) **Severity**: mild 5.5-5.9, moderate 6.0-6.4, severe ≥ 6.5 or any ECG changes or symptoms — affects urgency; (2) **Confirm**: rule out pseudohyperkalemia (hemolysis, prolonged tourniquet, fist clenching, K-EDTA contamination, thrombocytosis, leukocytosis) — repeat properly + plasma vs serum if concern; (3) **ECG indications**: K ≥ 6, symptoms, rapid change; look for peaked T waves → loss of P → wide QRS → sine wave (severe); ECG changes need IMMEDIATE treatment regardless of level; (4) **Causes**: - Renal — CKD, AKI; - **Medications** (most common modifiable in outpatient): ACEi/ARB, K-sparing diuretics (spironolactone, eplerenone, amiloride), MRA (finerenone), TMP-SMX, NSAIDs, heparin, beta-blockers, calcineurin inhibitors, succinylcholine; - Adrenal insufficiency; - Acidosis; - Hyperglycemia (insulin deficiency); - Cell breakdown (rhabdo, tumor lysis, hemolysis); - Excess intake usually with kidney impairment; (5) **Asymptomatic mild-moderate without ECG changes (this patient)** outpatient: - Dietary K restriction counseling (limit bananas, potatoes, tomatoes, oranges, melon, spinach, beans, salt substitutes — KCl content); - **Loop diuretic** (furosemide) — kaliuretic; - **K binders** — modern outpatient option: - **Patiromer (Veltassa)** — non-absorbable polymer; slow onset; good for chronic; allows continuation RAAS therapy; - **Sodium zirconium cyclosilicate (Lokelma)** — newer, faster onset; - **SPS (Kayexalate)** — older, GI side effects (concern bowel ischemia); replaced by newer agents often; - **Address underlying**: adjust offending medications (don''t blindly stop ACEi in HF/CKD — assess benefit-risk; new binders allow continuation); - **Treat acidosis** if present (bicarbonate selected); (6) **Severe (≥ 6.5 or ECG changes) — ED/hospital**: - **Calcium gluconate IV** — membrane stabilization (no K-lowering); - **Insulin + glucose** — shifts K intracellular; - **Beta-2 agonist** (albuterol nebulizer 10-20 mg) — shifts; - **Bicarbonate** if acidosis; - **Diuretic + K binder** for removal; - **Dialysis** for severe / refractory / ESRD; (7) **Re-evaluation**: recheck K in 1-2 wk; monitor with chronic treatment; (8) **RAAS continuation in CKD + HF**: balance with K management — emerging data K binders allow safe continuation with mortality benefit (don''t reflexively stop without alternative strategy); (9) **Patient education**: dietary, medication adherence, recognize symptoms (palpitations, weakness, paralysis); avoid salt substitutes (KCl); (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + nephrology + cardiology + dietitian + pharmacy

---

Hyperkalemia: severity + ECG + cause assessment. Pseudo? Mild-mod outpatient — dietary, loop diuretic, **new K binders (patiromer, ZS-9) allow RAAS continuation**. Severe → ED (Ca, insulin/glucose, beta-agonist, dialysis). Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 70 ปี HF + CKD eGFR 32 บน ACEi + spironolactone — labs routine K 6.1, ECG normal, asymptomatic';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Surgery first-line for all"},{"label":"B","text":"Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (AAOS + AAN)"},{"label":"C","text":"Long-term opioid for pain"},{"label":"D","text":"No treatment — observe"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore — common"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Carpal Tunnel Syndrome (AAOS + AAN): (1) **Diagnosis clinical** primarily: - Symptoms: median nerve distribution numbness/paresthesia (thumb, index, middle, lateral ring), often worse at night/with activities, hand shaking relief, weakness/clumsiness; - Provocative tests: Phalen (90 sec wrist flexion), Tinel (percuss median nerve), Durkan compression (most specific); thenar atrophy (severe/chronic); (2) **Risk factors**: F > M, age, obesity, pregnancy, DM, hypothyroidism, RA, dialysis, amyloidosis, repetitive wrist activities, vibration; (3) **Differential**: cervical radiculopathy (C6-7), thoracic outlet, ulnar neuropathy, peripheral neuropathy, brachial plexopathy; (4) **Workup**: - **Clinical diagnosis** sufficient many cases; - **EMG/NCS** — gold standard if uncertain, severe, surgical consideration, refractory, atypical, occupational/legal documentation; - **US** of median nerve — increasingly used (cross-sectional area ≥ 9-10 mm²); - **MRI** atypical; - **Labs** selectively: TSH (hypothyroid), HbA1c (DM), CBC + RF + ANA (autoimmune), vit B12; pregnancy assessment; (5) **Conservative management first** (mild-moderate): - **Wrist splinting** (neutral position) — especially nighttime; modest evidence; - **Activity modification + ergonomics**: keyboard, mouse, repetitive grip; workplace; - **NSAIDs / acetaminophen** for symptoms; - **Local corticosteroid injection** (1-2/yr) — short-term effective; - **Oral corticosteroid** short course — modest evidence; - **PT** — nerve gliding exercises; - **Address underlying**: treat hypothyroid, glucose control; (6) **Surgery** (open or endoscopic carpal tunnel release) for: - Severe / persistent / refractory; - Significant motor weakness or atrophy; - Severe sensory loss; - Failure conservative; - High-risk for permanent dysfunction; - Effective + outpatient procedure; (7) **Postoperative**: PT, gradual return to activity, expect improvement weeks-months; (8) **Pregnancy-related**: usually resolves postpartum — conservative (splint); (9) **Occupational considerations**: ergonomic assessment, workplace modification, workers'' compensation if applicable; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + hand surgeon (ortho or plastic) + PT/OT + occupational medicine if work-related

---

Carpal tunnel: clinical diagnosis (provocative tests). EMG/NCS if uncertain/surgical. Conservative first (splint, ergonomics, steroid injection, NSAIDs). Surgery for severe/refractory/motor weakness. Address underlying conditions. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 50 ปี — bilateral hand numbness + paresthesia at night, thumb/index/middle finger + lateral ring, weakness gripping × 6 mo';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Topical steroid only — even severe"},{"label":"B","text":"Psoriasis + Psoriatic Arthritis Management (AAD 2019 + 2023 update + ACR)"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid all biologics"},{"label":"D","text":"Single visit treatment"},{"label":"E","text":"No PsA screening"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Psoriasis + Psoriatic Arthritis Management (AAD 2019 + 2023 update + ACR): (1) **Diagnosis clinical**: well-demarcated erythematous plaques with silvery scale; typical distribution (extensor surfaces, scalp, nails, intergluteal); Auspitz sign (bleeding from removal scale); (2) **Severity classification**: - **Mild** (BSA < 3%); - **Moderate** (BSA 3-10%); - **Severe** (BSA > 10% or significant impact); - PASI (Psoriasis Area + Severity Index); - DLQI (impact); - **Comorbidity assessment**: psoriatic arthritis (~ 30%), CV (increased risk independent), metabolic syndrome, NAFLD, IBD, depression, anxiety, substance use; (3) **Psoriatic arthritis screening + diagnosis (CASPAR criteria)**: joint pain + psoriasis + nail dystrophy + dactylitis (sausage digit) + enthesitis + family history; PsA screening tools (PEST, PASE) at each visit; refer rheumatology + ortho; (4) **Treatment by severity**: - **Mild — topical**: - **Topical corticosteroids** — first-line (potency by site — high body, low face/groin/intertriginous); - **Vitamin D analogs** (calcipotriene); - **Combination** calcipotriene + betamethasone (Taclonex); - **Topical calcineurin inhibitor** (tacrolimus, pimecrolimus) — face, intertriginous; - **Topical retinoid** (tazarotene) — combo with steroid; - **Coal tar, salicylic acid** alternatives; - **Topical PDE-4 inhibitor (roflumilast)** — newer 2022; - **Topical aryl hydrocarbon receptor agonist (tapinarof — VTAMA)** — newer 2022; - **Moderate — phototherapy + systemic option**: - **NBUVB phototherapy** — first-line non-systemic; - **Excimer laser** localized; - **PUVA** alternative; - **Severe / refractory / PsA / nail / palmoplantar / scalp severe — systemic**: - **Methotrexate** — historical workhorse + PsA; LFT + CBC monitoring; folate; teratogen; - **Cyclosporine** short-term; - **Apremilast** (Otezla — PDE-4) oral; - **Acitretin** (retinoid) — teratogen 3 yr; - **Biologics** (revolutionary): - **TNF inhibitors** (adalimumab, etanercept, infliximab, certolizumab, golimumab) — also PsA + IBD; - **IL-17 inhibitors** (secukinumab, ixekizumab, brodalumab) — highly effective psoriasis; PsA; - **IL-23 inhibitors** (guselkumab, risankizumab, tildrakizumab) — highly effective, less frequent dosing; - **IL-12/23 inhibitor** (ustekinumab); - **JAK inhibitors** (deucravacitinib — TYK2 — oral; tofacitinib, upadacitinib for PsA); - **Comparing biologics**: head-to-head trials — IL-17 + IL-23 often higher efficacy than TNF for skin; TNF + JAK better for PsA + IBD; - **Screening before biologics**: TB, hepatitis B/C, HIV, vaccinations; (5) **Comorbidity management critical**: - **CV risk** assessment + management (independent ↑ ~ 20-50%) — statin + BP + DM + smoking + weight + exercise; - **PsA** — refer rheumatology, DMARD + biologic; - **Metabolic** + NAFLD; - **Mental health**: depression + anxiety + substance use; - **IBD**: screen + co-manage; - **Vaccinations**: avoid live on biologics; (6) **Lifestyle**: weight (psoriasis improves), Mediterranean diet, alcohol moderation, smoking cessation, stress management; (7) **Pregnancy**: certolizumab (preferred — minimal placental), other biologics individual; methotrexate teratogen 3 mo washout; (8) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + dermatology + rheumatology + cardiology + mental health + nutrition + GI + pharmacy

---

Psoriasis: severity stratified. Topical (steroid + vit D + calcineurin + newer roflumilast/tapinarof). Phototherapy. Systemic (MTX, biologics revolutionary — TNF + IL-17 + IL-23 + JAK). PsA screening + treatment. CV + metabolic + mental health comorbidity. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 35 ปี — chronic scaly erythematous plaques บน elbows + knees + scalp × 5 yr, BSA 8%, moderate; PsA + nail involvement';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No follow-up needed"},{"label":"B","text":"Chronic Otitis Media Management (AAO-HNS)"},{"label":"C","text":"Oral antibiotic long-term"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid ENT referral"},{"label":"E","text":"Surgery first-line"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Chronic Otitis Media Management (AAO-HNS): (1) **Chronic suppurative otitis media (CSOM)**: chronic TM perforation + intermittent/persistent otorrhea ≥ 2 wk; (2) **Cholesteatoma** — separate entity, can be congenital or acquired (more concerning): keratinized squamous epithelium in middle ear; can erode bone + cause complications (hearing loss, CN VII palsy, vertigo, meningitis, brain abscess, lateral sinus thrombosis); white/pearly mass in retraction pocket; CT temporal bone for evaluation + extent; (3) **Workup**: otoscopy + microsuction; pneumatic otoscopy / tympanometry (limited if perf); audiogram; cultures of drainage; CT temporal bone for cholesteatoma / complications; (4) **Medical management**: - **Topical antibiotic drops with steroid**: ofloxacin (Floxin), ciprofloxacin + dexamethasone (Ciprodex) — safe with perforation; - Avoid aminoglycoside drops with perforation (potentially ototoxic); - Aural toilet (debridement, suction); - Keep ear dry — water precautions; - Treat 7-14 d typically; chronic may need longer; (5) **Surgical management**: - **Cholesteatoma** — surgical removal (tympanomastoidectomy) — essential to prevent complications; - **Persistent perforation** with hearing loss or recurrent infection → tympanoplasty; - **Mastoiditis** acute or chronic — IV abx + surgery if severe; - ENT specialty management; (6) **Hearing loss management**: hearing aids, BAHA (bone anchored), CI selected; (7) **Complications watch**: - Mastoiditis; - Facial palsy; - Labyrinthitis (vertigo + sensorineural HL); - Petrositis (Gradenigo''s triad — otorrhea + retro-orbital pain + abducens palsy); - Meningitis; - Brain abscess; - Lateral sinus thrombosis; - Otitic hydrocephalus; - These are emergencies; (8) **Pediatric** considerations: chronic OM with effusion (OME) — tympanostomy tubes if persistent; speech delay; (9) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + ENT + audiology + speech pathology + neurosurgery if complications

---

Chronic OM / cholesteatoma: chronic perforation + otorrhea or pearly mass. Workup: otoscopy + audiogram + CT. Topical FQ + steroid drops safe with perforation. Cholesteatoma needs surgery. Complications serious. ENT referral. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 50 ปี — chronic ear fullness + hearing loss + occasional otorrhea ข้างขวา × 6 mo; perforation in TM on otoscopy + scant drainage';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Antibiotic for all croup"},{"label":"B","text":"Croup (Laryngotracheobronchitis) Pediatric (AAP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Long-term oral steroid"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid steroid in croup"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore stridor"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Croup (Laryngotracheobronchitis) Pediatric (AAP): (1) **Diagnosis clinical**: viral (parainfluenza most common, RSV, influenza, adenovirus, SARS-CoV-2 omicron specifically); 6 mo - 6 yr; barking cough, hoarse, inspiratory stridor; URI prodrome; (2) **Severity (Westley score)**: - **Mild**: no stridor at rest, no/mild WOB, normal mental status; - **Moderate**: stridor at rest, mild-moderate WOB; - **Severe**: marked stridor, retractions, agitation/lethargy, hypoxia → emergency; - **Imminent respiratory failure**: cyanosis, fatigue, decreased breath sounds; (3) **Differential** important to consider: - **Epiglottitis** (Hib — now rare with vaccine; bacterial; abrupt severe, drooling, tripod, toxic appearance — emergency airway + antibiotic); - **Bacterial tracheitis** — toxic + thick secretions; - **Foreign body** — sudden onset choking history; - **Anaphylaxis** — exposure + other symptoms; - **Retropharyngeal abscess**; - **Subglottic stenosis** congenital/acquired; - **Spasmodic croup**: recurrent, less viral, no fever; (4) **Workup**: clinical, no routine imaging; lateral neck X-ray (steeple sign — subglottic narrowing) only if uncertain; avoid distress; CBC/cultures not needed routine; (5) **Treatment**: - **Mild (this patient)**: - **Single dose dexamethasone 0.6 mg/kg PO/IM/IV (max 16 mg)** — strong evidence; reduces symptoms + return visits; equivalent oral/IM/IV; - Outpatient management with discharge; - Reassurance + return precautions; - **Cool mist** (older home remedy — limited evidence but used); - **Honey** for cough age > 1; - **Moderate**: - **Dexamethasone** + **nebulized racemic epinephrine** (2.25% 0.5 mL or L-epinephrine 5 mL 1:1000) — bridges 2-4 h until steroid effect; - Observe ≥ 2-4 h post-nebulizer (rebound possible); - Discharge if improved + reliable family; - **Severe**: - Above + admission; - Continuous nebulized epinephrine; - Higher dexamethasone or methylprednisolone; - Oxygen; - Heliox sometimes; - Intubation if respiratory failure; - ICU; - **Avoid agitation** in severe (worsens) — examine in caregiver''s lap; (6) **Antibiotics not indicated** for typical viral croup; bacterial tracheitis exception; (7) **Discharge criteria**: - No stridor at rest; - Normal O2 sat; - Tolerating PO; - Reliable family; - Education + return precautions; (8) **Return precautions**: stridor at rest, severe WOB, cyanosis, lethargy, inability to drink, persistent fever; (9) **Recurrent croup**: consider anatomic / GERD / asthma evaluation; ENT consideration; (10) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + ED + pediatrics + ENT if recurrent / atypical + anesthesia + ICU if severe

---

Croup: viral parainfluenza most common. Severity (Westley). Clinical diagnosis. **Single-dose dexamethasone** for all (mild oral, moderate-severe + neb epinephrine). Observe post-epi. Differentials important (epiglottitis, FB, bacterial tracheitis). Severe → admit. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'เด็กชาย 18 mo — barking cough + stridor + URI symptoms × 1 d; mild-moderate, no stridor at rest; no drooling, no toxic appearance';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Color-blind approach"},{"label":"B","text":"Health Disparities + Structural Racism (NAM + KFF + APHA)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single intervention"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid discussion of race"},{"label":"E","text":"Cultural competence achieved once"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Health Disparities + Structural Racism (NAM + KFF + APHA): (1) **Health disparities**: differences in health outcomes between populations, often systematic, avoidable, unjust; affecting race/ethnicity, SES, gender, sexual orientation, age, ability, geography, language; (2) **Structural racism**: ways societies foster racial discrimination through mutually reinforcing inequitable systems (housing, education, employment, healthcare, criminal justice, credit, etc.) — affects health beyond individual interactions; declared public health crisis by AMA + APA + CDC + multiple cities; (3) **Major disparities examples**: - **Maternal mortality** — Black women 3-4x higher; - **Infant mortality** — Black infants 2x; - **Life expectancy** — racial + geographic gaps (Black men ~ 4-5 yr lower; gap by ZIP code can be 20+ yr); - **COVID-19** — disproportionate impact communities of color; - **Heart disease + DM + asthma + hypertension** — disparities in incidence + outcomes; - **Cancer screening + treatment + survival** — disparities; - **Mental health + suicide** — disparities, especially youth (Black youth suicide rising); - **Pain management** — Black + Hispanic less likely receive adequate analgesia; - **LGBTQ+** — mental health, suicide, substance, healthcare avoidance; - **Disabilities** — access; - **Rural** — workforce, access, outcomes; (4) **Drivers + frameworks**: - **Social determinants of health (SDOH)** — 80% of health outcomes; - **Structural racism + discrimination** — see Bailey + Krieger, Williams; - **Toxic stress + allostatic load** biological consequences of chronic adversity; - **ACE (Adverse Childhood Experiences)** — lifetime health impact; - **Historical trauma** — Indigenous, Black, other communities; - **Implicit bias** healthcare providers — affects communication, diagnosis, treatment; - **Healthcare access + quality** — insurance, geography, language, cultural; - **Environmental injustice** — pollution, lead, food deserts, green space; - **Economic** — wealth gap; - **Education**; - **Criminal justice involvement**; - **Housing instability**; (5) **Evidence base growing**: - **Race as social construct, not biological** — eGFR race-correction recently removed; lung function reference equations being reconsidered; vBAC calculator removed race; - **Genetic ancestry vs racial identification** — distinct; - **Weathering hypothesis** (Geronimus) — accumulated stress accelerated aging in marginalized; - **Place-based health** — neighborhood matters; (6) **Approaches to address — multi-level**: - **Individual level**: - **Implicit bias training** — recognition; humility ongoing; - **Cultural humility** — see separate; - **Trauma-informed care**; - **Affirming care** (LGBTQ+, race, religion); - **Communication + language access**; - **Patient-centered + respectful care**; - **Practice level**: - **Diverse + competent workforce**; - **Equity-focused QI** — stratified outcomes, equity dashboard; - **Address SDOH** — screening + intervention + community partnerships; - **CHW + cultural broker programs**; - **Reduce barriers** (cost, transportation, language, hours, scheduling, virtual options); - **Community engagement** — co-design, advisory; - **System level**: - **Insurance + access** — Medicaid expansion, ACA; - **Workforce + GME funding** rural + underserved; - **Payment models** valuing equity; - **HIT + EHR** for equity; - **Quality measures** stratified; - **Policy + advocacy**: - **Healthcare policy** for coverage + access; - **Housing + employment + education + criminal justice + environmental** policy; - **Voting rights**; - **Climate justice**; - **Reparations + restorative justice**; (7) **Family medicine well-positioned**: relationships, community, longitudinal, holistic; (8) **Self-reflection + lifelong learning**: ongoing process; (9) **Allyship + advocacy** for marginalized communities; (10) **Resources**: NAM Communities in Action, Health Affairs racism series, NEJM Race + Medicine; AAFP Center for Diversity + Health Equity; KFF Disparities; Robert Wood Johnson; (11) **Multidisciplinary**: clinicians + administrators + patients + community + public health + policy + academia + advocacy + government + multiple sectors

---

Health disparities + structural racism: avoidable + unjust differences; major examples (maternal mortality, life expectancy, etc.). Race as social construct (eGFR de-racing). Drivers (SDOH, structural, ACEs, bias). Multi-level approaches (individual, practice, system, policy). Family medicine positioned. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง understanding + addressing health disparities + structural racism in primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"No place for complementary"},{"label":"B","text":"Complementary + Integrative Medicine (NCCIH + ACLM)"},{"label":"C","text":"All supplements safe"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid evidence-based integration"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore patient use"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Complementary + Integrative Medicine (NCCIH + ACLM): (1) **Definitions**: - **Complementary**: along with conventional; - **Alternative**: instead of (concerning); - **Integrative**: combination evidence-based + complementary; - **NCCIH** (National Center for Complementary and Integrative Health) — federal research arm; (2) **Categories**: - **Mind-body**: meditation, mindfulness, yoga, tai chi, qi gong, hypnosis, biofeedback, guided imagery; - **Nutritional**: herbal supplements, vitamins, minerals, special diets; - **Manipulative + body-based**: massage, chiropractic, osteopathic manipulation; - **Energy therapies**: Reiki, therapeutic touch, healing touch; - **Whole medical systems**: traditional Chinese medicine (acupuncture, herbs), Ayurveda, naturopathy, homeopathy; (3) **Evidence-based integrative — examples with reasonable evidence**: - **Mindfulness + meditation**: stress, depression, anxiety, chronic pain, hypertension, hot flashes, IBS, sleep; - **Yoga**: chronic LBP (ACP guideline), depression, anxiety, chronic stress; - **Tai chi**: falls prevention elderly, OA, fibromyalgia, mood; - **Acupuncture**: chronic pain (LBP, neck, OA, headache — meta-analyses + ACP + NICE), nausea (pregnancy, chemo), tension headache, fibromyalgia, smoking cessation; - **Massage therapy**: pain, anxiety, stress; - **Spinal manipulation (chiropractic/osteopathic)**: acute LBP (alongside other), some chronic LBP; safety considerations (rare vertebral artery dissection cervical); - **Probiotics**: AAD-associated diarrhea, IBS selected, Clostridioides difficile; specific strains important; - **Omega-3** fish oil: triglycerides, modest CV (IPE — Vascepa); supplements vs food; - **Vitamin D + Ca + others**: as deficient + bone health; - **Melatonin**: jet lag, circadian sleep disorders, mild insomnia, delayed sleep phase; - **Glucosamine + chondroitin**: knee OA — controversial, ACR/AF recommends against, AAOS limited support; - **St John''s Wort**: mild-moderate depression (drug interactions — induces CYP3A4); - **SAMe**: depression alternative; - **CoQ10**: statin myopathy modest, migraine prevention; - **Magnesium**: migraine prevention, leg cramps; (4) **Caution / limited evidence / safety concerns**: - **Herbal supplements**: variable quality + standardization (USP, NSF certified preferred); contamination; drug interactions; not FDA-regulated as drugs; - **St John''s Wort + many drugs**: induces CYP3A4 — affects OCP, warfarin, antiretroviral, immunosuppressants; - **Garlic + ginkgo + others**: bleeding risk + perioperative; - **Yohimbe, kava, ephedra, chaparral**: serious safety concerns; - **Homeopathy**: NHMRC + Cochrane — no effect beyond placebo; - **Chelation for CVD**: TACT trial mixed; not generally recommended; - **Detoxes + cleanses**: no evidence; - **Specific cancer cures, anti-vaccine, anti-immunology** claims; (5) **Approach in primary care**: - **Ask about use**: 30-40% use; don''t assume disclosure; non-judgmental; - **Educate**: about evidence + safety; - **Drug interactions check**: NCCIH, Memorial Sloan Kettering AboutHerbs, NatMed Pro; - **Integration with conventional**: many patients prefer integrative; combine evidence-based; - **Coverage**: some insurance covers acupuncture, chiropractic, massage; HSA-eligible; (6) **Major medical centers integrative programs**: most academic centers now have integrative medicine programs; (7) **Provider training resources**: Andrew Weil Center, AAFP, Integrative Health Coach Training; (8) **Cultural considerations**: many traditional practices have integrative role; respect + integrate; (9) **Lifestyle medicine overlap**: see separate; many integrative practices are lifestyle medicine; (10) **Pediatric integrative**: massage, mindfulness, yoga for children evidence; supplements caution; (11) **Quality + safety considerations** in recommending or referring; (12) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + integrative medicine specialist + nutrition + behavioral health + PT + complementary providers as appropriate

---

Integrative medicine: combine evidence-based + complementary. Evidence-based: mindfulness, yoga, tai chi, acupuncture (pain), massage, probiotics specific, omega-3, melatonin sleep, etc. Caution: herbal interactions (St John''s Wort, garlic), unregulated. Ask + educate + integrate safely. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง complementary + integrative medicine — evidence-based use primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Vaccines unsafe"},{"label":"B","text":"Vaccine Immunology + Development + Safety (CDC + ACIP + NIH)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single platform vaccines only"},{"label":"D","text":"No post-licensure monitoring"},{"label":"E","text":"Random adverse event attribution"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Vaccine Immunology + Development + Safety (CDC + ACIP + NIH): (1) **Immune response basics**: - **Innate**: rapid, non-specific (skin, mucosa, complement, phagocytes, NK cells); - **Adaptive**: specific, memory (T-cell + B-cell); - **B-cell** → antibodies (IgG, IgM, IgA, IgE); - **T-cell** → CD4 helper + CD8 cytotoxic; - **Memory cells** for rapid response on re-exposure; (2) **Vaccine types + how they work**: - **Live attenuated** (MMR, varicella, rotavirus, yellow fever, BCG): weakened pathogen replicates → strong immune response + long duration but contraindicated immunocompromised + pregnancy; - **Inactivated whole virus** (IPV, hepatitis A, rabies, some flu): killed pathogen safe in immunocompromised; usually need booster; - **Subunit / recombinant** (HepB, HPV, acellular pertussis, Shingrix, COVID): specific antigens; safe but less immunogenic — adjuvants used; - **Toxoid** (tetanus, diphtheria): inactivated toxin; - **Conjugate** (Hib, PCV, meningococcal): protein-conjugated polysaccharide for T-cell-dependent response in young children + better memory; - **Polysaccharide** (PPSV23): T-cell-independent; less effective < 2 yo; - **mRNA** (COVID Pfizer + Moderna): lipid nanoparticle delivers mRNA encoding spike protein; novel platform, rapid development, effective + safe in large populations; - **Viral vector** (J&J COVID, Oxford-AZ COVID, RSV): non-replicating modified virus; - **DNA** (animal use mostly); - **Adjuvants**: aluminum, oil-in-water, AS01 (Shingrix), CpG, others — enhance immune response; (3) **Vaccine development pipeline**: - **Pre-clinical** — in vitro + animal models; - **Phase 1** — small humans, safety + immunogenicity (~ 100); - **Phase 2** — expanded immunogenicity + dose (~ 100-300); - **Phase 3** — large efficacy trial (~ 10,000-50,000+); - **Approval** (FDA BLA, EUA in emergency); - **Phase 4** post-marketing surveillance; - **Recommendation** (ACIP for US); - Traditionally 10-15 yr; COVID vaccines accelerated to ~ 1 yr through parallel processes + emergency funding; (4) **Safety surveillance systems**: - **VAERS (Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System)** — passive reporting, signal detection; anyone can report; not causation but signal; - **VSD (Vaccine Safety Datalink)** — large EHR + claims database for safety studies; ~ 12 M people; - **CISA (Clinical Immunization Safety Assessment)** — expert consultation; - **PRISM (Post-Licensure Rapid Immunization Safety Monitoring)** — claims-based; - **v-safe** — COVID smartphone-based; - **International**: WHO, EMA, others; (5) **Common adverse events**: - Local: redness, swelling, soreness — common, mild; - Systemic: fever, headache, fatigue — common, mild, transient (especially mRNA COVID, Shingrix); - Allergic: rare anaphylaxis — observe post-injection; - Serious events: very rare; benefit-risk; - **Specific concerns historical**: - Wakefield MMR-autism fraud — disproven; - Thimerosal removed pediatric except multi-dose flu (precautionary, no harm shown); - HPV safety reassuring; - COVID mRNA — rare myocarditis (mostly young males, mostly mild self-limited, rate lower than COVID-19 myocarditis); - COVID J&J — rare TTS (thrombosis with thrombocytopenia syndrome) led to limited use; - Rotavirus + intussusception (first version Rotashield withdrawn, current OK); - Oral polio + VAPP (rare paralysis) led to IPV switch in US; (6) **Vaccine injury compensation**: - **VICP** (Vaccine Injury Compensation Program) — no-fault for routine vaccines; - **CICP** (Countermeasures Injury Compensation Program) — COVID, pandemic countermeasures; - Funded by excise tax on vaccines; (7) **Vaccine hesitancy** (see separate); (8) **Future vaccines + technology**: - **mRNA platform**: COVID success accelerating other (flu, RSV, HSV, HIV, malaria, cancer therapeutic vaccines); - **Universal flu vaccine**; - **HIV + TB + malaria** — major need; - **Cancer vaccines** (HPV preventive established; therapeutic emerging); - **CMV, RSV, EBV**; - **Vaccine delivery innovation**: needle-free, transdermal, microneedles, oral, thermostable; (9) **Equity in vaccine access + uptake**: domestic + global; COVAX international; vaccine equity gaps; (10) **Vaccine communication** (see hesitancy); (11) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + nursing + pharmacy + public health + research + manufacturer + regulator + international + community

---

Vaccine science: immune response basics. Types (live, inactivated, subunit, conjugate, mRNA, viral vector). Development phases. Safety surveillance (VAERS, VSD, v-safe). Common AEs vs serious rare. VICP. Hesitancy. Future mRNA + other. Equity. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง vaccine immunology + how vaccines work + safety surveillance';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Ignore environmental factors"},{"label":"B","text":"Environmental Health + Climate Change + Primary Care (CDC + AAFP + Lancet Countdown)"},{"label":"C","text":"No counseling needed"},{"label":"D","text":"Single exposure focus"},{"label":"E","text":"Climate not health issue"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Environmental Health + Climate Change + Primary Care (CDC + AAFP + Lancet Countdown): (1) **Environmental exposures** affecting health: - **Air pollution** (PM2.5, ozone, NO2, SO2): - **Indoor + outdoor**; - CV, respiratory (asthma, COPD), cancer (lung), stroke, dementia, premature mortality; - 7 million deaths/yr globally; - Wildfire smoke increasing; - **Water**: - Lead in old pipes (Flint, others) — children especially; - Arsenic; - Microbial; - Industrial chemicals (PFAS — ''forever chemicals'' increasingly regulated, ubiquitous); - **Soil + food**: - Pesticides (organophosphates, neonicotinoids); - Heavy metals (lead, mercury, cadmium); - Mycotoxins; - Food packaging chemicals (BPA, phthalates); - **Chemicals**: - Endocrine disruptors (phthalates, BPA, dioxins, PFAS, parabens); - Industrial + occupational; - Household products; - **Radiation**: - Ionizing (medical, occupational, environmental); - Non-ionizing (UV, RF); - **Noise pollution**: hearing loss, CV, sleep, cognitive; - **Light pollution**: circadian disruption; - **Lead** — preventable + persistent (paint, water, contamination): children screening + abatement; (2) **Climate change health impacts (Lancet Countdown framework)**: - **Heat** — heatstroke, deaths, CV strain, occupational, elderly + vulnerable; - **Extreme weather**: hurricanes, floods, fires — direct mortality + displacement + chronic disease decompensation + mental health + infection; - **Vector-borne disease** range expansion: dengue, malaria, Lyme, West Nile, chikungunya, Zika; - **Foodborne** + **waterborne** disease; - **Food + water insecurity**; - **Air quality** worsening — wildfires, ground ozone; respiratory + CV; - **Allergies + asthma** worsening (pollen seasons longer, more intense); - **Mental health**: climate anxiety, eco-grief, PTSD, displacement; - **Migration + conflict** — displacement, war, healthcare disruption; - **Maternal-fetal**: heat + air pollution + preterm + LBW; - **Disproportionate impact on vulnerable**: low-income, elderly, children, communities of color, global South; **climate justice**; (3) **Healthcare sector contribution** to climate: - ~ 5% global emissions (8.5% US); - Energy, supply chain, pharmaceuticals, transportation, waste; - **Healthcare Without Harm + Practice Greenhealth** initiatives; - Inhaler emissions (MDIs vs DPIs); - Anesthetic gases (desflurane, NO2); - Reduce, reuse, recycle; - Sustainable food in hospitals; - Greener transportation; (4) **Primary care role**: - **Patient counseling**: - Lead screening + abatement; - Air quality awareness (AQI, masks, air purifier); - Water + food safety; - Sun protection + UV; - Chemical exposure reduction; - Heat illness prevention (vulnerable patients); - Disaster preparedness; - Climate-related health discussions; - **Clinical adaptation**: - Chronic disease management considering climate (HF + heat, asthma + air quality); - Mental health support (climate anxiety, displacement); - Outbreak preparedness; - Telemedicine for access during disasters; - **Workplace + community**: - Healthcare facility sustainability; - Procurement; - Advocacy; (5) **Specific population concerns**: - **Children** — most vulnerable to environmental + developmental; - **Pregnant** — fetal vulnerability + LBW + preterm; - **Elderly** — heat, air, chronic disease; - **Outdoor workers** — heat, sun, air, exposures; - **Low-income + marginalized** — disproportionate exposure + less resilience; - **Indigenous communities** — environmental justice + sovereignty; (6) **Reporting + public health**: lead, occupational exposures, certain conditions; (7) **Resources**: NIEHS, EPA, CDC NCEH, AAFP Climate + Health, Climate + Health website (UCSF, Yale, others); Medical Society Consortium on Climate + Health; (8) **Advocacy**: climate action critical health intervention; physician voice powerful; (9) **Multidisciplinary**: clinicians + public health + environmental health professionals + community + government + advocacy + academia + private sector

---

Environmental health: air, water, soil, chemicals, lead, radiation, noise. Climate change major + growing health threat — heat, extreme weather, vector-borne, food/water insecurity, mental health, climate justice. Healthcare contributes 5%. PC role: counsel, adapt, advocate. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง environmental health + climate change + primary care role';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single source for all"},{"label":"B","text":"EBM + Research Implementation in Practice (BMJ + JAMA + GRADE)"},{"label":"C","text":"Random clinical decisions"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid guidelines"},{"label":"E","text":"Always follow expert opinion"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** EBM + Research Implementation in Practice (BMJ + JAMA + GRADE): (1) **EBM definition (Sackett)**: integration of best evidence + clinical expertise + patient values for clinical decisions; (2) **5As process**: - **Ask** clinical question (PICO — Patient + Intervention + Comparison + Outcome); - **Acquire** best evidence (efficient search — PubMed Clinical Queries, point-of-care tools); - **Appraise** validity + impact + applicability; - **Apply** to patient; - **Assess** outcomes — feedback loop; (3) **Hierarchy of evidence** (with caveats): - Systematic reviews / meta-analyses (Cochrane, others); - RCT; - Cohort studies (prospective > retrospective); - Case-control; - Cross-sectional; - Case series + reports; - Expert opinion; - **Real-world evidence + pragmatic trials** growing importance; - Hierarchy applies for treatment questions; other questions may have different optimal designs; (4) **Critical appraisal frameworks**: - **CASP** (Critical Appraisal Skills Programme); - **JAMA Users'' Guides**; - **STROBE, CONSORT, PRISMA** reporting standards; - **GRADE** (Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development + Evaluation) — quality of evidence + strength of recommendation; modern standard for guidelines; (5) **Statistical concepts essential**: - **p-value, CI, NNT/NNH, RR/OR/HR, sensitivity/specificity/LR/predictive values, AUC, Hazard ratios**; - **Statistical vs clinical significance**; - **Effect size + magnitude**; - **Heterogeneity** in meta-analyses; - **Subgroup analyses** — hypothesis-generating; - **Surrogate vs hard outcomes**; - **Composite endpoints** — examine components; - **Funding bias + publication bias** — caution; (6) **Point-of-care resources**: - **UpToDate** (most popular subscription); - **DynaMed** (alternative); - **BMJ Best Practice**; - **Essential Evidence Plus**; - **AAFP, ACP, NICE, USPSTF** guidelines; - **PubMed Clinical Queries**; - **MDCalc** for clinical calculators; - **Specialty society guidelines**; (7) **Clinical practice guidelines (CPG)**: - GRADE methodology; - Strong vs conditional recommendations; - Quality of evidence (high to very low); - Consider applicability + context + values; - Be cautious — quality + bias variable; - National Guideline Clearinghouse archived; trustworthy alternatives; - Conflicts of interest concern; - Don''t blindly apply — individualize; (8) **Implementation science**: - **Translating evidence to practice** — major gap; ~ 17 yr from evidence to widespread adoption; - **Implementation science frameworks** (RE-AIM, CFIR, others); - **De-implementation** of low-value care; - **PDSA cycles** in practice; - **Practice facilitation + academic detailing**; - **Audit + feedback**; - **Clinical decision support**; - **Practice + culture change**; (9) **Common pitfalls + cognitive biases**: - **Confirmation bias**; - **Anchoring**; - **Availability heuristic**; - **Premature closure**; - **Outcome bias**; - **Status quo bias**; - Strategies: differential diagnoses, time pressure awareness, second opinions, decision support; (10) **Patient + shared decision**: integrate evidence + patient values; decision aids; (11) **Lifelong learning + MOC**: ABFM + ABIM + others; CME requirements; competency-based; (12) **Research literacy + skepticism**: - Reading abstracts/headlines insufficient; - Examine methods + funding + conflicts; - **Pre-prints** require caution; - **Single studies** often don''t change practice — replication + meta-analysis; - **Sponsorship effects**; (13) **Real-world data + AI**: - **Real-world evidence (RWE)** growing — EHR, claims, registries; - **AI for evidence synthesis, decision support, prediction** — emerging + caution about bias + validity; (14) **Equity in research + evidence**: - **Underrepresentation** of women, racial/ethnic minorities, elderly, pregnant in trials; - **External validity** for your patient population; - **Generalizability** considerations; (15) **Multidisciplinary EBM**: PCP + librarians + research + quality + IT + administration + patients + community + payers

---

EBM + research implementation: 5As + PICO + hierarchy + GRADE. Statistical literacy. Point-of-care tools (UpToDate). Critical appraisal — funding + bias. CPGs with caution + individualize. Implementation science — close evidence-practice gap. Cognitive biases. Lifelong learning. Equity in research. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง implementing research + EBM in busy primary care + clinical practice guidelines';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Ignore technology"},{"label":"B","text":"Health Informatics + AI in Primary Care (AMIA + ONC + WHO)"},{"label":"C","text":"Random AI use"},{"label":"D","text":"No human oversight"},{"label":"E","text":"Single application"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Health Informatics + AI in Primary Care (AMIA + ONC + WHO): (1) **Health informatics**: science of how data, information, knowledge, wisdom support healthcare + decision-making; includes EHR, clinical decision support, interoperability, analytics, AI; (2) **Modern EHR functions**: - Documentation; - Order entry (CPOE); - Results review; - Decision support (alerts, order sets, templates); - Population health (registries, dashboards); - Patient portal + messaging; - Telehealth integration; - Referral management; - Billing + coding; - Quality reporting; - Analytics; (3) **Interoperability progress**: - **FHIR** (Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources) standard — widespread adoption; - **TEFCA** (Trusted Exchange Framework + Common Agreement) — national interoperability framework; - **CMS + ONC interoperability + information blocking rules** (Cures Act) — patient API access mandatory; information blocking prohibited; - **HIEs** (Health Information Exchanges) — regional/state; - **Direct messaging**; (4) **AI applications in primary care** — rapidly emerging: - **Ambient AI scribes** (Nuance DAX, Suki, Abridge, others) — listen to encounter + draft note + orders; major productivity + burnout reduction; - **Clinical decision support AI**: risk prediction (Epic Sepsis Score, deterioration, readmission), diagnostic assistance (differential, imaging), treatment recommendations; - **Imaging AI**: radiology (chest X-ray, mammography, fracture), dermatology (skin lesion classification), ophthalmology (diabetic retinopathy — IDx-DR FDA-approved); - **Pathology AI**: emerging; - **NLP for chart review**: case identification, quality measure, registry, social determinants extraction; - **Predictive analytics**: high-risk patient identification, no-show prediction, panel management; - **Chatbots + virtual assistants**: patient triage, FAQ, follow-up; - **Drug discovery + clinical trials**; - **Patient-facing**: symptom checkers (Ada, Buoy, others), health coaches, mental health (Woebot, Wysa); - **Voice + conversational AI**; (5) **Generative AI + LLMs in healthcare**: - **GPT-4, Claude, Med-PaLM, others** — explosive growth; - **Use cases**: documentation, patient communication drafts, literature summary, education, decision support; - **Risks**: hallucination, bias, privacy, liability, overreliance; - **Validation + governance + oversight** needed; - **Augment not replace** clinician judgment; (6) **AI considerations**: - **Bias in training data** → biased outputs (e.g., underrepresented populations); audit + correct; - **Explainability + transparency** — black box concerning; - **Validation + monitoring** ongoing; - **Workflow integration**; - **Provider trust + adoption**; - **Patient trust + consent**; - **Regulation evolving** (FDA SaMD — Software as Medical Device); - **Equity** — risk of widening disparities if poorly designed; - **Liability**; - **Cost + access**; (7) **Patient digital health tools**: - Apps for self-management (Diabetes — many; mental health — Headspace, Calm; medication reminders; menstrual; weight); - Wearables (Apple Watch, Fitbit, Garmin) — increasingly clinical-grade (ECG, AFib detection, fall, sleep, SpO2); - Connected devices (BP, glucose, scales); - Patient-reported outcomes (PROMs) integration; - Digital therapeutics (FDA-approved — Pear AKILI ADHD, Somryst insomnia, others); (8) **Telemedicine** — see separate; (9) **Cybersecurity + privacy**: - HIPAA compliance; - Ransomware attacks epidemic on healthcare; - Patient data breaches; - Cyber insurance; - Patient privacy in apps + wearables (FTC, FDA); (10) **Health equity in digital health**: - **Digital divide** — access, broadband, literacy, language; - **Algorithmic bias** — affects marginalized; - **Equity-centered design**; - **Multiple modalities** (digital + non-digital); (11) **Provider wellness + informatics**: - **EHR burden** top driver of burnout; - **Ambient AI scribes** game-changer for documentation; - **EHR optimization**; - **Usability** improving; (12) **Future direction**: - **Generative AI everywhere**; - **Continuous health monitoring** (wearables + sensors); - **Precision medicine** (genomics + AI); - **Patient empowerment** + self-management; - **Workforce transformation**; - **Equity considerations** central; (13) **Multidisciplinary informatics**: clinicians + informaticians + data scientists + IT + administration + patients + community + regulators + vendors + academia

---

Health informatics + AI: EHR + interoperability (FHIR, TEFCA). AI applications — ambient scribes (game changer), CDS, imaging, NLP, predictive, generative LLMs. Considerations — bias, explainability, validation, equity, liability. Patient digital tools. Cybersecurity. Burnout reduction. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง health informatics + AI in primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"More testing always better"},{"label":"B","text":"Quaternary Prevention + Choosing Wisely (Marc Jamoulle + ABIM Foundation)"},{"label":"C","text":"Defensive medicine acceptable"},{"label":"D","text":"Patient request mandates"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore harms"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Quaternary Prevention + Choosing Wisely (Marc Jamoulle + ABIM Foundation): (1) **Quaternary prevention** (Jamoulle): protect patients from harms of medical intervention itself; avoid overdiagnosis + overtreatment + overuse; primum non nocere; (2) **Overdiagnosis + overdetection**: identifying conditions that would not have caused harm — patient labeled as ill; common in cancer screening + incidentalomas; psychological + treatment harms; (3) **Common areas of overuse + low-value care**: - **Cancer screening**: - Screening older adults with limited life expectancy (mammogram, colonoscopy, PSA, Pap); - Aggressive treatment of low-risk cancers (active surveillance better — prostate, DCIS, low-grade thyroid); - Screening outside age guidelines; - **Imaging**: - Routine imaging for headache, LBP, syncope without red flags; - CT for minor head injury; - Pre-op CXR; - Routine EKG asymptomatic; - **Lab tests**: - Annual TSH asymptomatic; - Routine vitamin D; - Routine basic labs annual exam without indication; - **Medications**: - Antibiotics for viral; - PPI long-term without indication; - Antipsychotic in dementia; - Polypharmacy elderly; - Routine antihistamines for cold; - Statin in low-risk elderly with limited life expectancy; - **Procedures**: - Arthroscopy for OA without mechanical sx; - Vertebroplasty for osteoporotic fractures (controversial); - Routine spinal fusion for chronic LBP; - Pre-op + pre-procedural unnecessary clearance; - **Hospital + ICU**: - Continuous monitoring not indicated; - Phlebotomy daily routine; - Restraints; - Antibiotic over-broad; - End-of-life ICU when goals palliative; - **Mental health**: - SSRI for mild grief; - Long-term benzodiazepines; - Stimulant for situational; - **Pediatric**: - CT for minor head trauma low-risk; - Antibiotic for viral; - **Geriatric**: - Tight glycemic + BP control elderly with comorbidity; - PSA + colonoscopy elderly; - Polypharmacy; (4) **Choosing Wisely Campaign** (ABIM Foundation 2012+): - 80+ specialty societies; - > 600 ''don''t do'' recommendations; - Promotes conversation between clinicians + patients; - Lists for primary care (AAFP, ACP, AAP) + each specialty; - International expansion; (5) **Drivers of overuse**: - **Defensive medicine** — fear of missing or being sued; - **Patient expectations** — perceived need for test/treatment; - **Reimbursement** — FFS rewards volume; - **Cultural** — more is better; - **Time pressure** — easier to order than discuss; - **Lack of clinical decision support**; - **Direct-to-consumer + medical marketing**; - **Pharma + device industry** influence; - **Asymmetric incentives**: harms underweighted; - **Cascade effect** — incidentalomas lead to more testing; (6) **De-implementation strategies**: - **Audit + feedback**; - **Clinical decision support** alerts; - **Shared decision making + decision aids**; - **Patient + clinician education**; - **Payment reform** (value-based); - **Practice + culture change**; - **Guidelines emphasizing both ''do'' and ''don''t''**; - **Practice transformation**; - **Quality measurement** including overuse; (7) **Communication strategies for patients**: - Acknowledge concerns + take seriously; - Explain rationale; - Share information about harms + benefits; - Decision aids; - ''Watchful waiting'' positive framing; - Specific recommendations; - Follow-up plan; - Empathic + collaborative; (8) **Equity + overuse paradox**: - Some communities have **both** underuse + overuse simultaneously; - Address both; - **Underuse** in marginalized often more harmful than overuse; (9) **High-value care** — provide care of high value (benefit relative to cost + harms): - High-value care principles; - **ACP High Value Care Initiative**; - Includes prevention, screening, diagnosis, treatment, end-of-life; (10) **Cost transparency + financial toxicity**: - Patients suffering from healthcare costs; - Discuss cost when possible; - Choose less costly when comparable benefit; - Generic over brand; (11) **Family medicine well-positioned**: relationship, comprehensive view, often non-procedural focus, primary care first principle; (12) **Multidisciplinary**: clinicians + patients + administrators + payers + policymakers + societies + advocacy

---

Quaternary prevention: avoid harms of medical intervention. Overuse + low-value care widespread (screening older, imaging routine, abx viral, polypharmacy elderly, etc.). Choosing Wisely. Drivers (defensive, expectations, FFS, time, culture). De-implementation. Shared decision. Equity nuanced. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident ถามเรื่อง quaternary prevention + avoiding overdiagnosis + overtreatment + low-value care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Document every detail"},{"label":"B","text":"Documentation Efficiency + Burden Reduction (AAFP + AMA + ONC)"},{"label":"C","text":"No documentation efficiency efforts"},{"label":"D","text":"Copy entire prior notes"},{"label":"E","text":"Solo physician model"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Documentation Efficiency + Burden Reduction (AAFP + AMA + ONC): (1) **EHR documentation = top driver of burnout** + dissatisfaction; PCPs spend ~ 2 h documentation per 1 h direct patient care (''pajama time''); (2) **2021 E/M coding changes (CMS)** — major win: - Documentation now based on **MDM (Medical Decision-Making)** OR **total time** (not bullet count of history + exam); - Reduces unnecessary documentation; - History + exam at clinically necessary level; - MDM elements: number/complexity of problems + data reviewed/ordered + risk of complications; - Total time includes pre-, intra-, post-visit on date of service; (3) **MDM levels for E/M codes**: - **99202 / 99212 — straightforward**: minimal problems + minimal data + minimal risk; - **99203 / 99213 — low complexity**: 1-2 stable chronic, 1 acute uncomplicated; - **99204 / 99214 — moderate complexity**: 1+ chronic with exacerbation OR 2+ stable chronic OR undiagnosed problem; data review; moderate risk (Rx management, MDM); MOST COMMON outpatient PCP code; - **99205 / 99215 — high complexity**: severe exacerbation, multiple comorbidity, severe risk (escalation of Rx, hospitalization decision, drug toxicity); (4) **Time-based coding alternative** when time > MDM threshold: - 99202: 15-29 min; - 99203: 30-44 min; - 99204: 45-59 min; - 99205: 60-74 min; - **Prolonged services** add-on codes (99417, G2212); - Includes documentation, chart review, results, calls, coordination on date; (5) **Add-on codes valuable** to capture work beyond E/M: - **G0444 / G0442** — screening (depression, alcohol); - **99490 / 99487 / G2058** — CCM (chronic care management); - **99495 / 99496** — TCM (transitional care management); - **99497 / 99498** — ACP (advance care planning); - **99484 / 99492-99494** — BHI / CoCM; - **99453 / 99454 / 99457** — RPM (remote patient monitoring); (6) **Strategies for efficient documentation**: - **SmartPhrases + templates** for common conditions, but personalized + accurate; - **Voice recognition** (Dragon Medical, M*Modal); - **Ambient AI scribes** (Nuance DAX, Suki, Abridge, Heidi, others) — listen to encounter + draft note + orders + bill suggestions; major productivity boost + burnout reduction; growing rapidly; - **Real human scribes** (in-person or virtual) — alternative; - **Team documentation** — MA pre-charting + room prep + reconciliation; - **Workflow optimization** — pre-visit planning, room layout, EHR settings; - **Concurrent vs delayed documentation** — concurrent during/immediately after visit better; - **Limit copy-forward** — keeps notes lean + reduces errors; - **Inbox management protocols**; - **Asynchronous + portal messaging** with team triage; - **Standing orders + protocols**; - **EHR optimization + personalization**: shortcuts, favorites, dotphrases; (7) **What to include in good notes**: - Clinical reasoning; - Patient story + context; - Shared decisions; - Plan + follow-up; - Communication with team / family / specialists; - Relevant social + functional + values; - Avoid: bloat, irrelevant boilerplate, copy-forward of outdated info, copying entire labs; (8) **Documentation for quality + billing**: - **HCC coding** (Hierarchical Condition Categories) for risk adjustment Medicare Advantage; document all chronic conditions annually with specifics; - **Quality measures** documentation; - **Medical necessity**; - **Avoid undercoding** common; (9) **Open notes (OpenNotes movement + Cures Act)**: - Patients have access to clinical notes; - Write ''for the patient'' — clear, non-judgmental, accurate; - Avoid stigmatizing language; - Improves engagement + trust + accuracy; - Address concerns about sensitive topics (mental health, substance use, IPV) — guidance available; (10) **Audit + feedback** on documentation + coding; (11) **Provider wellness link**: - Reducing documentation burden = wellness intervention; - AI scribes major emerging help; - Team-based care + workflow optimization; - Practice culture supports thoughtful (not excessive) documentation; (12) **Regulatory + future**: - **Continued reduction in documentation requirements**; - **Interoperability** reduces re-documentation; - **AI-driven workflow**; - **Outcome-focused measurement** vs documentation-heavy; (13) **Multidisciplinary**: clinicians + scribes/AI + IT + coders + billers + administration + nursing + MA + patients (open notes)

---

Documentation: 2021 E/M MDM or time-based. Add-on codes (CCM, TCM, ACP, BHI, RPM) capture work. **Ambient AI scribes major emerging** for burden reduction. Open notes — write for patient. Team docs. EHR optimization. HCC for risk adjustment. Wellness link. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — improving documentation efficiency + reducing burden in primary care + leveraging AI';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Reactive care only"},{"label":"B","text":"Population Health Analytics + Data-Driven Primary Care (CMS + IHI)"},{"label":"C","text":"No data analytics"},{"label":"D","text":"Single metric tracking"},{"label":"E","text":"Avoid risk stratification"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Population Health Analytics + Data-Driven Primary Care (CMS + IHI): (1) **Population health management (PHM)**: proactively manage health outcomes of a defined population — panel, attributed members, community; data + analytics critical; (2) **Data sources**: - **EHR** — clinical, encounters, results, problem lists, medications; - **Claims** — utilization, costs, full picture across settings (esp ACO); - **Registries** — chronic disease, specific populations; - **HIEs** — cross-organization; - **Patient-reported data** — surveys, PROMs, wearables, portal; - **SDOH data** — neighborhood, equity-focused; - **Public health data** — outbreaks, environmental; - **Genetic + genomic** emerging; - **Social media + non-traditional sources**; (3) **Analytics capabilities**: - **Descriptive** — what happened? (dashboards, reports); - **Diagnostic** — why? (drill-down, root cause); - **Predictive** — what will happen? (risk stratification, ML); - **Prescriptive** — what should we do? (decision support); (4) **Risk stratification**: - **High-risk identification** — top 5% of users + costs; - **Risk algorithms** — CMS-HCC, ACG, DxCG, Milliman, custom; combines diagnoses, age, sex, prior utilization, sometimes SDOH; - **Rising risk** — moderate complexity, intervention can prevent escalation; - **Stable + healthy** — wellness + prevention; - **Apply interventions tailored to risk tier**; (5) **Care gaps identification**: - **HEDIS + similar measures** — preventive + chronic disease quality; - **Lapsed care** — overdue screening, vaccination, lab, follow-up; - **Medication adherence** — refill data; - **Specialty follow-up**; - **Action**: registry-based outreach via call, text, patient portal, mail; standing orders; team-based; (6) **Disease registries**: DM, HTN, asthma, CHF, depression, COPD, mental health, substance use, special populations; updated regularly; (7) **Care management programs**: - **High-risk care management** — RN/SW assigned; structured intervention; - **Disease management** — condition-specific; - **Transitional care management** (post-hospital); - **Behavioral health integration** + CoCM (see separate); - **Care coordination** with specialists, hospital, community; (8) **SDOH integration**: - **Screening tools** (PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, others); - **Documentation** in EHR; - **Resources + referrals** (Unite Us, NowPow, FindHelp); - **Address actively** — partnership with social services + community; - **Equity-focused analytics**: stratify outcomes; (9) **Quality measurement + reporting**: - **HEDIS, CMS Stars, MIPS, custom**; - **Performance dashboards** — patient, panel, practice, system levels; - **Real-time vs retrospective**; - **Equity-stratified**; (10) **Cost + utilization analytics**: - **Total cost of care** per member; - **Utilization** — ED, hospitalization, readmission, imaging, specialty; - **Pharmacy spend**; - **Identify outliers** + opportunities; (11) **Predictive analytics + ML**: - **Risk of hospitalization, readmission, mortality**; - **Disease onset prediction** (e.g., HF, AFib, sepsis); - **No-show prediction**; - **Sepsis early detection** (controversial — Epic Sepsis Score limitations); - **Validation + bias** essential; (12) **Patient engagement analytics**: - **Portal usage, telehealth, app engagement**; - **PROMs** integration; - **Survey results** (CAHPS, custom); (13) **Workflow integration**: - **Pre-visit planning** — care gaps + chronic disease management; - **In-visit** — decision support, registries, alerts; - **Post-visit** — outreach, follow-up; - **Between-visit** — care management, monitoring; (14) **Provider performance + practice transformation**: - **Benchmark + variation analysis**; - **PDSA + improvement projects**; - **Audit + feedback**; - **Recognition + incentives**; (15) **Equity + bias considerations**: - **Stratify all metrics** by race, ethnicity, language, SES; - **Address algorithmic bias**; - **Community engagement** in design; - **Avoid widening disparities** through interventions; (16) **Workforce + culture**: data literacy, quality team, leadership commitment; (17) **Technology infrastructure**: EHR + data warehouse + analytics platform; specialized tools (Health Catalyst, Arcadia, Innovaccer, Epic Cogito, others); (18) **Privacy + security**: HIPAA, data governance; (19) **Multidisciplinary**: clinicians + data analytics + quality + IT + care management + administration + patients + community + payers

---

Population health analytics: data sources (EHR, claims, registries, SDOH). Capabilities (descriptive, predictive, prescriptive). Risk stratification + tailored intervention. Care gaps identification + outreach. Disease registries. Care management. SDOH. Equity-stratified. Workflow integration. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — population health analytics + data-driven primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Random satisfaction tracking"},{"label":"B","text":"Patient Experience + Satisfaction Primary Care (CAHPS + AHRQ + IHI)"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid feedback"},{"label":"D","text":"Patient feedback irrelevant"},{"label":"E","text":"Single intervention"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Patient Experience + Satisfaction Primary Care (CAHPS + AHRQ + IHI): (1) **Patient experience vs satisfaction**: - **Experience**: what happened (objective + subjective); - **Satisfaction**: how patient felt (more variable); - Both matter; experience drives satisfaction + outcomes; (2) **Why patient experience matters**: - Outcomes — adherence, follow-through, engagement; - Quality (Triple Aim); - Reduces malpractice (most malpractice = communication failures); - Reimbursement — CMS value-based payment includes; - Reputation + word of mouth; - Provider satisfaction reciprocal; (3) **Measurement**: - **CAHPS** (Consumer Assessment of Healthcare Providers + Systems) — standardized national surveys; multiple versions (clinician + group, PCMH, hospital); - **PROMs** (patient-reported outcome measures); - **NPS** (Net Promoter Score) — commercial; - **Custom surveys**; - **Mystery shopping**; - **Patient advisory councils** + qualitative; - **Real-time feedback** (kiosks, text); (4) **Key drivers of patient experience**: - **Access** — appointment availability, hours, wait times, telemedicine; - **Communication** — listening, explaining, time spent, partnership; - **Care coordination** — handoffs, between visits, with specialists; - **Provider relationship** — continuity, knowing the patient; - **Office staff interactions** — phones, front desk, MA, nursing; - **Physical environment** — clean, comfortable, accessible, welcoming; - **Patient + family engagement** — shared decision-making, materials, portal; - **Affordability + financial discussions**; - **Cultural humility + respect**; - **Patient safety**; (5) **Common dissatisfaction sources**: - **Waiting time** — appointment + in-office; - **Communication failures** + feeling unheard; - **Rushed visits**; - **Billing issues**; - **Lack of follow-up** on results, plans; - **Coordination breakdowns**; - **Phone access difficult**; - **Inadequate explanation**; - **Disrespect or bias**; - **Financial surprises**; (6) **Improvement strategies**: - **Access**: same-day + open access scheduling, after-hours, telemedicine, walk-in options, group visits; - **Wait time**: workflow optimization, accurate scheduling, communication if delays; - **Communication training**: empathic listening, NURSE skills, teach-back, shared decision-making; - **Continuity**: panel size + assignment, follow-up with same provider, care teams; - **Team-based care**: relationships beyond physician; - **Patient portal optimization**: secure messaging, schedule, results, refills, bill pay; - **Cultural humility + equity**: training, diverse workforce, language access, affirming care; - **Patient education + materials**: plain language, accessible, multiple formats; - **Financial transparency + assistance**: discussing costs, sliding scale, assistance programs; - **Closed-loop on results + follow-up**; - **Patient + family advisory councils** for input; - **Service recovery** when problems occur — acknowledge, apologize, fix, learn; - **Concierge-level touches** as appropriate (callback, attentive); (7) **Provider behavior**: - Sit at eye level; - Make eye contact (not at screen); - Listen actively + interrupt less (avg 11 sec); - Acknowledge emotions; - Use patient''s name; - Explain rationale + recommendations; - Confirm understanding; - Ask ''what questions do you have?''; - Thank patient at end; - Follow through on commitments; (8) **Staff training + culture**: - **Customer service training** for all staff; - **Empowerment** to resolve issues; - **Recognition** for good service; - **Address turnover + burnout** (linked to patient experience); (9) **Specific populations**: - **Limited English** — interpreter services + accommodations; - **Disabilities** — accessibility; - **Pediatric** — child + parent considerations; - **Mental health + sensitive issues** — trauma-informed + safe environment; - **LGBTQ+** — affirming; - **Older adults** — pace + considerations; (10) **Outcomes link**: better experience → better adherence + outcomes + reduced utilization; (11) **Equity in patient experience**: - **Disparities in experience** documented (e.g., race, language); - **Stratify metrics**; - **Address gaps**; (12) **Provider wellness link**: positive experiences for both — bidirectional; reduce burnout helps both; (13) **Multidisciplinary patient experience team**: leadership + clinicians + staff + patients (advisory) + quality + facilities + IT + customer service

---

Patient experience: matters for outcomes + reimbursement + reputation. CAHPS measurement. Drivers (access, communication, coordination, relationship, staff). Improvement (access, training, continuity, portal, transparency, advisory). Provider behavior. Equity in experience. Wellness link. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — improving patient experience + satisfaction in primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Medical care only"},{"label":"B","text":"Social Prescribing + SDOH Integration (NHS + WHO + US emerging)"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid SDOH discussion"},{"label":"D","text":"No community partnerships"},{"label":"E","text":"Random screening"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Social Prescribing + SDOH Integration (NHS + WHO + US emerging): (1) **Social prescribing** (originated NHS UK, growing US): primary care refers patients to non-medical community-based services for biopsychosocial needs; (2) **Common social prescriptions**: - **Food**: meal delivery (Meals on Wheels), food pantry, SNAP/WIC assistance, food prescriptions (produce vouchers), nutrition counseling; - **Housing**: housing assistance, supportive housing, weatherization, lead abatement, mold remediation, Section 8, homelessness services; - **Transportation**: ride services (Lyft, Uber Health), public transit assistance, paratransit; - **Financial**: benefits enrollment (Medicaid, SNAP, SSI, EITC), financial counseling, debt management, employment assistance; - **Legal**: medical-legal partnerships (housing, immigration, benefits, family); - **Education**: GED, literacy, English language; - **Childcare**: subsidies, programs; - **Connection**: community groups, religious communities, peer support, intergenerational, hobby + interest; - **Exercise + activity**: parks programs, gym referrals (SilverSneakers, YMCA), walking groups, gardening, tai chi; - **Mental health adjuncts**: art, music, dance, drama therapy, mindfulness, gardening, nature exposure; - **Spiritual + religious**: chaplaincy, faith communities, meditation, contemplative practices; (3) **Implementation models**: - **Screen first**: standardized SDOH tools (PRAPARE, AHC HRSN, ''Health Begins''); - **Care navigator / community health worker / link worker**: bridges referrals + follows up; - **Community resource platforms**: Unite Us, NowPow, FindHelp.org, Aunt Bertha — directories + referrals + closed-loop tracking; - **Embedded community resources** — co-location of social services, legal, financial; - **Co-design with community**; (4) **Why integrate SDOH**: - **80% of health outcomes from SDOH** (vs 20% medical); - Address root causes; - Improve outcomes + equity; - Reduce utilization + costs (some evidence); - Patient-centered care; - Required for value-based care; - Some payment models incentivize; (5) **CMS + Medicaid increasingly addressing**: - **Z codes** documentation in EHR (ICD-10 Z55-Z65 — SDOH); - **Medicaid 1115 waivers** for SDOH; - **In Lieu Of services** Medicaid; - **CMS Innovation Center models** (REACH ACO, others) incentivize; - **Quality measures** including SDOH; (6) **Evidence base**: - **Food prescriptions** — improved DM, BP, food security; - **Housing interventions** (Housing First) — better mental health, substance use, hospitalization, cost; - **Transportation** — improved appointment attendance + outcomes; - **Medical-legal partnerships** — improved health + cost; - **Community health workers** — multiple conditions; - **Social prescribing UK** — improved well-being, reduced primary care visits, some cost reduction; (7) **Workforce**: - **Community Health Workers (CHWs)** — bridge community + healthcare; trained; growing recognition + reimbursement; - **Social workers**; - **Care navigators / patient advocates**; - **Promotores / lay health workers**; - **Peer support specialists** (especially mental health, substance use, lived experience); - **Medical-legal partners**; (8) **Community partnerships essential**: - Food banks, housing organizations, schools, faith-based, parks + recreation, libraries, employers, government agencies, social services, advocacy; - **Asset-based community development** approach — leverage strengths; - **Coalitions** + collaboratives; - **Community input + governance**; (9) **Ethical + privacy considerations**: - Asking sensitive SDOH questions — trauma-informed; - Risk of stigma if SDOH discovered + not addressed; - Confidentiality with community partners; - Data sharing agreements; (10) **Equity + community engagement**: - **Power dynamics** + structural racism in design; - **Community co-design**; - **Hire from community**; - **Equity in resource access**; (11) **Sustainability + funding**: - Operational challenges; - Reimbursement evolving; - Grant funding; - Health system investment + benefit; - Policy advocacy; (12) **Quality measurement + outcomes**: - Patient experience; - Resource connection + utilization; - Health outcomes (chronic disease, mental health, hospitalization); - Equity stratified; - Cost; (13) **Resources**: SIREN (UCSF Social Interventions Research + Evaluation Network), Aligning for Health, AAFP EveryONE Project, Camden Coalition; (14) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + CHW + social work + behavioral health + community partners + government + nonprofits + faith + business + patients + advocacy

---

Social prescribing + SDOH: 80% outcomes from social factors. Screen (PRAPARE), connect via navigator + platforms (Unite Us). Common prescriptions (food, housing, transportation, financial, social, exercise, mental health). Evidence-based interventions. CHW + community partnerships. CMS Z codes + payment. Equity + community co-design. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital — implementing social prescribing + SDOH integration in primary care + community partnerships';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Single patient focus"},{"label":"B","text":"Multi-Generational Family-Centered Chronic Disease (AAFP + family medicine principles)"},{"label":"C","text":"Avoid family involvement"},{"label":"D","text":"Random caregiver support"},{"label":"E","text":"No multi-generational view"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Multi-Generational Family-Centered Chronic Disease (AAFP + family medicine principles): (1) **Family medicine unique value**: care entire family unit; understand interactions + dynamics; relationship continuity; address upstream + interconnected health; (2) **Multi-generational chronic disease** common: - **Children**: T1DM, asthma, ADHD, autism, mental health, obesity, allergies, dental; - **Parents + working age**: T2DM, HTN, lipid, obesity, depression, anxiety, substance use, autoimmune, chronic pain; caregivers; - **Grandparents + elderly**: dementia, frailty, multimorbidity, isolation; care recipients; - **All ages**: vaccinations, preventive, mental health, dental, vision; (3) **Family-level assessment**: - **Genogram** 3 generations — medical, mental health, social, relationships; - **Family roles + dynamics**; - **Caregiving structure + burden**; - **Communication patterns**; - **Financial + housing**; - **Cultural + religious**; - **ACEs across generations**; - **Strengths + resilience**; (4) **Coordinated visits + communication**: - **Family meetings** for major decisions, transitions, end-of-life; - **Sibling visits** or coordinated; - **Shared appointments** for elderly + caregiver; - **Care plans visible to family** with consent; - **Multi-generational EHR view** (within HIPAA); (5) **Caregiver support critical**: - **Identify + screen** caregivers in patient visits (Zarit Burden); - **Caregiver-specific visits** with own goals; - **Education + training**; - **Respite resources** (in-home, adult day care, short-term residential); - **Support groups** (specific to condition — Alzheimer''s Association, etc.); - **Mental health support** — caregiver depression, anxiety; - **Practical assistance**: caregiving leave (FMLA), financial planning, legal (POA, advance directives); - **Self-care + boundaries**; - **Recognize caregiver burnout, abuse, neglect**; - **Sandwich generation**: caring for both children + parents — high stress; - **Hidden caregivers**: spouses, children, distant family; (6) **Pediatric chronic disease in family context**: - **T1DM (this scenario)**: family involvement essential — coordinated diabetes management, sibling impact, parental burnout, transition to self-management adolescence + adult care; - **Family-based behavioral interventions** evidence (T2DM, asthma, mental health, weight management); - **School integration**; - **Anticipatory guidance**: developmental + chronic disease; - **Mental health screening** for child + family; (7) **Adult chronic disease in family context**: - **Spouse/partner involvement**: motivation, support, shared decision-making; - **Spouse health affected** by partner illness (caregiver burden, increased risk own illness); - **Sexual + intimacy** considerations; - **Children affected**: especially if young + parental chronic illness; - **Financial impact** on family; - **Lifestyle changes** family-wide (diet, exercise, smoking) more sustainable; (8) **Geriatric in family context**: - **Caregiver-centered model** of care; - **Adult children involved** in decisions (with patient consent + when capacity declines); - **Sibling coordination**; - **Long-distance caregiving**; - **Transitions**: aging in place vs assisted living vs nursing home — family discussions; - **Advance care planning + family meetings**; - **End-of-life care**; - **Bereavement** affects whole family; (9) **Family-based interventions evidence**: - **CBT + family therapy**; - **Family-based diabetes education**; - **Family asthma programs**; - **Family-based weight management**; - **Family meals + nutrition**; - **Family physical activity**; - **Parenting programs** (PCIT, Triple P) for behavior; - **Caregiver education + support**; - **Genetic family counseling**; (10) **Cultural + diverse families**: - **Definitions of family** vary — chosen family, extended, multigenerational households, LGBTQ+ families, single-parent, blended, foster + adoptive; - **Cultural roles** + decision-making vary; - **Language + literacy**; - **Religious + spiritual** beliefs about health + healing; - **Affirming care** for diverse family structures; (11) **Adverse family experiences**: - **IPV**; - **Child abuse + neglect**; - **Elder abuse**; - **Substance use in family**; - **Mental illness affecting family**; - **Divorce + separation**; - **Death**; - **Trauma transmission**; - **Mandatory reporting** when applicable; - **Trauma-informed family-centered care**; (12) **Resources**: family caregiver alliance, AARP caregiving, Alzheimer''s Association, NAMI for family of mentally ill, specific disease foundations, MyAgingParent, etc.; (13) **Multidisciplinary family-centered**: family medicine + relevant specialty + behavioral health + social work + nursing + dietitian + caregivers + family + community + faith + legal + financial

---

Multi-generational family-centered: family medicine unique value. Genogram + family assessment. Coordinated visits + communication. **Caregiver support critical**. Pediatric / adult / geriatric chronic disease in family context. Family-based interventions evidence. Cultural diversity. Adverse experiences. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ครอบครัว — 12-yo with T1DM + parents with chronic conditions + grandparents with dementia + caregiving burden; multi-generational family-centered chronic disease management';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Ignore work history"},{"label":"B","text":"Workplace Wellness + Occupational Health Integrative (NIOSH + ACOEM + WHO)"},{"label":"C","text":"No workplace integration"},{"label":"D","text":"Random wellness programs"},{"label":"E","text":"Single intervention"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Workplace Wellness + Occupational Health Integrative (NIOSH + ACOEM + WHO): (1) **Workplace impact on health**: - Working-age adults spend 1/3 of waking hours at work; - Workplace exposures + culture significant determinant of health; - Workplace wellness can leverage scale + structure; - Integration with primary care; (2) **Common occupational exposures + concerns**: - **Physical**: ergonomic (MSK injuries), noise (hearing loss), heat/cold, radiation, vibration, falls, motor vehicle (commercial drivers), needle sticks + bloodborne (healthcare); - **Chemical**: solvents, metals, pesticides, fumes, particulates, endocrine disruptors, asbestos (historical); - **Biological**: infectious (healthcare, food, animal handling, public-facing) — COVID-19 huge example; - **Psychosocial**: workplace stress, harassment, discrimination, demands, lack of control, work-life conflict, bullying, violence; - **Shift work**: circadian disruption, sleep, CV, GI, cancer (IARC 2A); - **Sedentary work**: prolonged sitting; - **Computer-related**: vision, MSK, repetitive strain; - **Pregnancy + reproductive**: certain exposures + accommodations; (3) **OSHA + regulatory framework**: - **OSHA** standards + enforcement; - **NIOSH** research + recommendations; - **MSHA** mining; - **Worker''s compensation** state-based; - **EEOC** (discrimination + ADA accommodations); - **FMLA** (family + medical leave); (4) **Occupational history taking** in primary care: - All jobs (current + past); - Specific exposures; - Onset of symptoms relationship; - Work hazards; - PPE use; - Workplace incidents; - Co-workers similarly affected; - Job demands + accommodations; - Returns to work; (5) **Specific occupational conditions**: - **MSK injuries**: ergonomics + return-to-work; - **Hearing loss** noise-induced — prevention + hearing conservation programs; - **Asthma** work-exacerbated or sensitizer-induced; - **Dermatitis** occupational; - **Mental health + burnout** + workplace stress + violence; - **Heat-related illness**; - **Bloodborne pathogen exposure** (healthcare needle stick); - **Pesticide exposure** (agricultural workers); - **Pneumoconioses** (silicosis, asbestosis, coal worker''s, byssinosis); - **Hand-arm vibration syndrome**; - **Carpal tunnel** work-related; - **Lead, mercury, other heavy metal poisoning**; (6) **Workplace wellness programs**: - **Comprehensive programs**: health risk assessment, biometric screening, lifestyle coaching, smoking cessation, weight management, exercise, nutrition, stress, financial wellness; - **Evidence mixed**: some show modest health improvement + ROI; selection bias common; - **Equity considerations**: not all employees benefit equally; access + privacy concerns; - **Voluntary + privacy** important; - **Tobacco-free workplace**, **healthy food options**, **lactation rooms** (ACA required), **exercise facilities**; - **Employee Assistance Programs (EAP)** — confidential counseling, financial, legal, family; - **Mental health benefits + access**; (7) **Return to work** after illness/injury: - **Modified duty / light duty** preferred over total disability when possible; - **Functional capacity evaluation**; - **Graduated return-to-work**; - **Accommodations** under ADA; - **Communication with employer** (with consent); (8) **Workers'' Compensation**: - Insurance system for work injuries; - Documentation requirements; - Disability ratings; - Treatment authorization; - Litigation considerations; - State-specific; (9) **Vulnerable workers**: - **Low-wage**; - **Immigrant + undocumented** (special protections + barriers); - **Temporary + gig workers**; - **Healthcare workers** (high physical + emotional + infectious + violence risks); - **Older workers**; - **Pregnant workers** (PWFA 2022 expanded accommodations); - **People with disabilities** (ADA); (10) **Pandemic / COVID-19 workplace**: - PPE; - Telework expansion; - Ventilation; - Vaccination policies; - Quarantine + sick leave; - Long COVID; - Mental health impact; (11) **Climate change + workplace**: heat stress increasing; outdoor workers; (12) **Public health + workplace** intersection: - **Workplace COVID outbreaks**; - **Smoke-free workplace** legislation; - **Workplace as health promotion site**; (13) **Provider role**: - **Recognize occupational causes**; - **Counsel + accommodations**; - **Coordinate workers'' compensation**; - **Workplace contact** with consent; - **Report** required conditions (lead, certain infectious, occupational injuries); - **Advocate for safe workplaces**; (14) **Resources**: NIOSH, OSHA, ACOEM, AOEC + others; (15) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + occupational medicine + employer + HR + safety + employee + union (where applicable) + ADA coordinator + workers'' comp + community + advocacy

---

Workplace wellness + occupational health: huge impact on health. Exposures (physical, chemical, biological, psychosocial, shift work). Occupational history. Specific conditions. Workplace wellness programs (mixed evidence + equity). Return to work. Workers'' comp. Vulnerable workers. Pandemic + climate. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Hospital + employer — workplace wellness + occupational health primary care';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Random sedative"},{"label":"B","text":"Bereavement + Grief — Primary Care (NHPCO + APA)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single visit only"},{"label":"D","text":"Avoid emotional discussion"},{"label":"E","text":"Discharge — get over it"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Bereavement + Grief — Primary Care (NHPCO + APA): (1) **Grief is normal universal response to loss**, not pathology; primary care often first contact + ongoing support; (2) **Types of loss requiring grief support**: - Death (spouse, parent, child, sibling, friend); - Anticipatory (chronic/terminal illness); - Disenfranchised (LGBTQ+, miscarriage, pet, dementia, addiction); - Trauma + sudden death; - Mass casualty + disaster; - Estrangement; - Loss of health, function, role, dreams; (3) **Normal grief manifestations**: - **Emotional**: sadness, anger, guilt, anxiety, relief, numbness, loneliness, yearning; - **Physical**: fatigue, sleep, appetite, somatic symptoms, immune effects (broken heart syndrome, takotsubo); - **Cognitive**: difficulty concentrating, preoccupation, denial, confusion; - **Behavioral**: withdrawal, crying, restlessness, dreams; - **Spiritual**: questioning faith, meaning, anger at higher power; - **Social**: changes in relationships + role; (4) **Theories of grief** (no rigid stages, individualized): - **Kübler-Ross stages** (originally for dying, applied to grief — controversial application): denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance; - **Worden''s tasks**: accept reality, process pain, adjust to environment without, find way to memorialize + move forward; - **Dual process model** (Stroebe + Schut): oscillation between loss-oriented + restoration-oriented; - **Continuing bonds** (Klass): healthy ongoing connection; - **Meaning-making** (Neimeyer); (5) **Distinguishing normal vs complicated grief**: - **Normal**: intensity decreases over time; functions; finds meaning; bonds with deceased + new connections; - **Acute grief**: weeks-months, intense; - **Integrated grief**: continues lifetime; - **Prolonged grief disorder (PGD)** DSM-5-TR (2022 added): - Persistent intense grief > 12 mo adults / > 6 mo children; - Identity disruption; - Disbelief; - Avoidance; - Emotional pain; - Difficulty engaging; - Numbness; - Loss of meaning; - Loneliness; - ~ 7-10% bereaved; - Risk factors: traumatic death, close attachment, prior trauma, lack of support; - **Treatment**: complicated grief therapy (Shear), targeted CBT, group, medications selected; - **Major depressive disorder** comorbid + distinct from normal grief — treat both; - **PTSD** especially traumatic death; (6) **Suicide risk** elevated in bereaved (especially spouse, parent loss, first weeks-months, suicide bereavement); screen; (7) **Primary care role**: - **Continued relationship + presence**; - **Active listening + validation** — primary intervention; - **Education** — normalize grief; - **Screening** — depression, suicidal ideation, complicated grief; - **Pharmacotherapy** — judicious; SSRI for comorbid depression or PGD with depression; avoid benzodiazepines (mask grief, dependence); short-term sleep aid if needed; - **Referral** — therapist, complicated grief specialist, support groups, hospice bereavement; - **Address physical concerns** that may arise; - **Spiritual support** referral; (8) **Bereavement support resources**: - **Hospice bereavement** programs — 13 months Medicare hospice benefit; - **Support groups**: condition-specific, demographic-specific (widows, parents of children who died, suicide loss survivors — TAPS for military, Compassionate Friends for child loss, others); - **Online communities**; - **Faith communities**; - **Caring contacts** (cards, calls); - **Workplace bereavement leave** + support; - **Anniversary reactions** awareness; (9) **Children + adolescents grieving**: - Developmentally specific responses; - Age-appropriate explanations; - Continued routines + reassurance; - School involvement; - Children of grieving parents — additional support; - **Resources**: National Alliance for Children''s Grief, Dougy Center; (10) **Special populations**: - **Pregnant + perinatal loss** (miscarriage, stillbirth, neonatal) — often disenfranchised; specific support (Star Legacy, others); - **LGBTQ+** — disenfranchised grief if not recognized; chosen family; - **Suicide loss survivors** — high risk PGD + own suicide; specific support (AFSP); - **Substance use loss** — disenfranchised; - **Mass casualty / disaster** — community response; - **Healthcare worker grief**: cumulative loss, moral injury, peer support; - **COVID-19 bereaved** — large group, often complicated by isolation + restrictions; (11) **Cultural + spiritual considerations**: - Diverse rituals + practices; - Mourning periods + customs; - Respect + accommodate; - Religious traditions + clergy involvement; - Continuing bonds vary culturally; (12) **Provider self-care + own grief**: - Accumulating losses; - Patient deaths; - Peer support + debriefing; - Acknowledge own grief; (13) **Multidisciplinary**: PCP + behavioral health + chaplaincy + social work + bereavement specialists + community resources + support groups + family + friends + faith community + workplace

---

Bereavement / grief: normal universal response. Types + manifestations. Distinguish normal vs prolonged grief disorder (DSM-5-TR 2022). Comorbid depression + PTSD + suicide risk. PC role: presence, validation, education, screening, judicious meds (SSRI for comorbid), referrals. Resources + support groups. Special populations. Cultural humility. Provider self-care. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'ผู้ป่วยอายุ 60 ปี — recent death of spouse × 2 mo + sleep + appetite + sadness + isolation; family worried';

update public.mcq_questions
set choices = '[{"label":"A","text":"Status quo continuation"},{"label":"B","text":"Future of Primary Care + Family Medicine (NAM Implementing High-Quality Primary Care 2021 + AAFP)"},{"label":"C","text":"Single-discipline future"},{"label":"D","text":"Ignore technology"},{"label":"E","text":"Ignore equity"}]'::jsonb,
    explanation = '<!-- choice-detail --> **ตัวเลือก B (รายละเอียด):** Future of Primary Care + Family Medicine (NAM Implementing High-Quality Primary Care 2021 + AAFP): (1) **NAM 2021 Report ''Implementing High-Quality Primary Care''** — comprehensive vision + action plan: 5 objectives: - Pay for primary care teams; - Train where people live + work; - Design IT to support primary care; - Make high-quality primary care available to every individual + family; - Ensure that high-quality primary care is implemented in the US; (2) **Vision of primary care future**: - **Universal access** for all; - **Continuous, integrated, team-based, accessible, accountable care**; - **Patient-centered + family-centered**; - **Community-engaged + equity-focused**; - **Whole-person + integrated behavioral health + SDOH**; - **Technology-enabled** but not technology-driven; - **Adequately resourced + valued**; - **Diverse + well-supported workforce**; (3) **Payment + value transformation**: - **From FFS to capitation + value-based** payment; - **Hybrid models** (base + performance + outcomes); - **Direct primary care (DPC)** + concierge growing; - **Primary care spend** increased (currently US ~ 5-7% of healthcare $, target 12%+ recommended); - **Equity-centered payment**; - **Risk adjustment**; - **Population health alignment**; (4) **Workforce transformation**: - **Severe shortage + maldistribution** ongoing; - **Team-based care** at all members'' top-of-license; - **APPs + pharmacists + behavioral health + CHWs + scribes + AI** expanded roles; - **GME funding + expansion** rural + underserved + family medicine; - **Loan repayment + Title VII + NHSC**; - **Recruitment + retention**; - **Burnout reduction** central; - **Diversity + URM workforce**; - **International medical graduates** integration; (5) **Technology + AI integration**: - **Ambient AI scribes** game-changer for documentation; - **AI-enabled decision support** + diagnostic; - **Telemedicine + remote monitoring** integrated; - **Predictive analytics**; - **Asynchronous + virtual + hybrid care**; - **Patient-empowering technology** (apps, wearables, portals); - **Generative AI** assistance; - **Interoperability + FHIR + cross-system data**; - **Equity-centered** technology; - **Avoid widening digital divide**; (6) **Behavioral health integration full scaling**: - **Collaborative Care Model** universal; - **Mental health + substance use** integrated routine; - **Address mental health workforce shortage**; - **Address stigma**; - **MOUD access**; (7) **SDOH + community integration full integration**: - **Universal SDOH screening**; - **Resource connection + community partnerships**; - **CHW + medical-legal partnerships standard**; - **Address structural drivers** of health; - **Equity-focused metrics**; (8) **Health equity central**: - **Structural racism addressed**; - **Workforce diversity reflects communities**; - **Stratified outcomes + accountability**; - **Community engagement + co-design**; - **Address determinants**; - **Climate justice** integrated; (9) **Climate adaptation + sustainability**: - **Healthcare sector decarbonization**; - **Climate-resilient practices**; - **Climate health counseling**; - **Advocacy**; (10) **Lifespan + family medicine value**: - **Maternal-child + adolescent + adult + geriatric continuity**; - **Family unit care**; - **Multi-generational + community-centered**; (11) **Specific innovations + trends**: - **Hospital-at-home** + **post-acute** in home; - **Direct primary care** + **concierge** subscription models; - **Digital therapeutics**; - **Group + community-based care** scaling; - **Hybrid telemedicine + in-person**; - **Microhospitals + emergency centers**; - **Retail clinics + pharmacy clinics** integrated or competing; - **Big tech + tech-enabled primary care** (Amazon One Medical, Walgreens VillageMD, CVS Oak Street, etc.); - **Risk-bearing primary care** organizations; (12) **Education transformation**: - **Competency-based + outcomes-focused**; - **Community-based + ambulatory training**; - **Interprofessional education**; - **Diversity + community partnerships**; - **Address debt + equity in admissions**; - **Family medicine pipeline** + visibility; (13) **Research + innovation**: - **PCORI** (Patient-Centered Outcomes Research); - **Primary care research network**; - **Pragmatic + real-world**; - **Community-based participatory**; - **Implementation science**; (14) **Global health solidarity**: - **Universal health coverage** worldwide; - **Climate justice**; - **Pandemic preparedness**; - **Workforce migration ethics**; - **Health diplomacy**; (15) **Wellness + sustainability**: - **Clinician + team well-being** central; - **Reducing administrative burden**; - **Joy in practice**; - **Career sustainability**; (16) **Family medicine as cornerstone**: relationship-centered, comprehensive, lifespan, community, equity-focused, integrated — uniquely positioned for future primary care; (17) **Multidisciplinary collaborative future**: clinicians + APPs + pharmacy + behavioral health + dental + community + public health + tech + administration + patients + community + government + academia + private sector + advocacy

---

Future of primary care (NAM 2021): universal access + team-based + integrated + technology-enabled + equity-focused. Payment + value transformation. Workforce. AI + tech. Behavioral health + SDOH integration. Climate + global health. Wellness. Family medicine cornerstone. Multidisciplinary.'
where exam_source = 'AI-generated-board-seed'
  and board_specialty = 'family_medicine'
  and scenario = 'Resident — vision for future of primary care + family medicine — 2030 + beyond';

